 and other stone stele with high relief faces honoring the deceased. Size: 5.6 in. W x 9.375 in. H (14.2 cm x 23.8 cm).','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/Fine-South-Arabian-Alabaster-Head-of-Bearded-Male/77f-fine_south-09.5.19-artemi','lot-art.com'),(47,'0- _25_p085_f13f7dbe','Selling antiquities, ancient and ethnographic art online since 1993, Artemis Gallery specializes in Classical Antiquities (Egyptian, Greek, Roman, Near Eastern), Asian, Pre-Columbian, African / Tribal / Oceanographic art. Each stands slightly forward on its realistic hoof with two claws displayed, the cuboid slightly set over the back of the hoof rather than directly over it, with two naturalistic projections from the back, showing that the artisans who sculpted the molds to create these feet paid close attention to the details of bull anatomy. Four matching, more-than-life-sized cast bronze bull hooves, each capped by a large, cuboid shape, and with two have projecting slots atop the cuboid for attachment. The cuboid projections and slots on two of them suggest that they were made to hold a table or altar rather than a full statue of a bull. Another possibility is that these feet were part of a naos - a simple rectangular temple form - as in an example found near Haoulti, which had four feet shaped like bull\'s hooves, two pointing forward, and two pointing back, supporting a base that held a niche decorated with ornamentation. Size of each (all are relatively similar): 5.75\" W x 11\" H (14.6 cm x 27.9 cm) What might these massive hooves have graced? 1st millennium BCE to early 1st millennium CE, probably later in the period based on the lead weight, which was a later technological innovation to stabilize monumental statuary. For example, the sandstone offering table found at Swada and now at the Louvre (AO 31930) has an animal\'s head on the left and feet terminating in bull\'s hooves.',85,NULL,'','Four cast bronze bull hooves, each with a cuboid upper element and two naturalistic projections at the back, probably intended as supports for a table, altar, or naos. Each measures 5.75 in. W x 11 in. H (14.6 cm x 27.9 cm) and is dated to the 1st millennium BCE to the early 1st millennium CE.','Four cast bronze bull hooves, each more-than-life-sized and similarly proportioned, with a realistic hoof form showing two claws, a cuboid element set slightly over the back of the hoof, and two naturalistic projections from the rear. Two of the examples have projecting slots on top of the cuboid, indicating attachment points. The form suggests that they may have served as supports for a table or altar rather than for a full bull statue; another possibility is that they belonged to a naos, a simple rectangular temple form. Each measures 5.75 in. W x 11 in. H (14.6 cm x 27.9 cm). The group is dated broadly to the 1st millennium BCE to the early 1st millennium CE, probably later in that range based on the lead weight mentioned in the source text.','https://www.bidsquare.com/online-auctions/artemis-gallery/set-of-4-sabean-bronze-bull-hoof-supports-2251316','bidsquare.com'),(48,'0- _25_p086_d1991843','[ translate ] South Arabian A Group of five alabaster figures To be sold without reserve Provenance: Private Collection of Dr. LOT 297 South Arabian A Group of five alabaster figures To... From the Dr Mohammed S Farsi Collection Dimensions: Ranging from 10 in. Mohammed Said Farsi (1936-2019), acquired between 1960-90 at Christie\'s, Sotheby\'s and Mayfair Galleries London.',86,NULL,'','Group of five South Arabian alabaster figures, ranging in height from 10 in., from the Dr Mohammed Said Farsi Collection.','Group of five alabaster figures, South Arabian, from the Dr Mohammed Said Farsi Collection. The figures range in height from 10 in. Provenance given as the private collection of Dr. Mohammed Said Farsi (1936-2019), acquired between 1960 and 1990 at Christie’s, Sotheby’s, and Mayfair Galleries, London.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/South-Arabian-A-Group-of-