haped eyes, an arched browline, and closed lips.','Head, alabaster, Ancient South Arabian Sabaean, c. 2nd century BC. Fine carved alabaster head of a man in high relief, with wide-open almond-shaped eyes, an arched browline, and closed lips. The source text identifies the object as Ancient South Arabian, Sabaean, and notes a provenance statement that is incomplete in the provided text.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/Ancient-South-Arabian-SABAEAN-Alabaster-head-c2nd-century-BC/84-ancient_south-20.10.24-palmyra','barakatgallery.com'),(57,'0- _10_p003_2e6655ff','Ancient Figurines & Statues Greek Terracotta Seated Figure £ 1,150.00 Ancient Figurines & Statues Hellenistic Terracotta Female Head £ 295.00 Deities & Demi-Gods Roman Bronze Diana Figurine £ 1,300.00 Deities & Demi-Gods Roman Bronze Winged Cupid Figure £ 1,695.00 Rare South Arabian Alabaster Camel £ 695.00 A realistically carved figurine of a dromedary in alabaster: it stands four-square with head erect. Ancient Figurines & Statues Greek Terracotta Seated Figure £ 1,150.00 Ancient Figurines & Statues Hellenistic Terracotta Female Head £ 295.00 Deities & Demi-Gods Roman Bronze Diana Figurine £ 1,300.00 Deities & Demi-Gods Roman Bronze Winged Cupid Figure £ 1,695.00 Ancient South Arabia is a geographical label referring to a region occupied by six semitic kingdoms: Sabaʼ, Qatabān, Ma‘īn, Ḥaḍramawt, the Kingdom of Awsan, and the Himyarite Kingdom. Additional information Culture Near Eastern Region Near East (Western Asiatic) Stone Alabaster Related products Coptic Textiles Coptic Textile Fragment with Zoomorphic Decoration £ 270.00 Cat & Feline Figurines Marble of Lion Devouring Animal Head £ 495.00 Coptic Textiles Leaf Shaped Coptic Panel with Dancer £ 295.00 Storage Vessels Tang Dynasty Ink Stone Vessel £ 1,800.00 Customers also bought Maceheads Western Asiatic Sumerian Alabaster Macehead £ 495.00 you may also like... Home » All Antiquities » Ancient Figurines & Statues » Camel Figurines » Rare South Arabian Alabaster Camel Rare South Arabian Alabaster Camel £ 695.00 A realistically carved figurine of a dromedary in alabaster: it stands four-square with head erect. Out of stock Description Additional information Ancient South Arabia is a geographical label referring to a region occupied by six semitic kingdoms: Sabaʼ, Qatabān, Ma‘īn, Ḥaḍramawt, the Kingdom of Awsan, and the Himyarite Kingdom. The territory of these kingdoms corresponds to a modern-day area including Yemen, and extending into Oman, north to the Arabian oasis of Dedan, to Ethiopia, and even as far along as the East African Coast, into modern Tanzania. Their depiction is thus endowed with significance in several contexts: in religious rituals, as mythical creatures, and as incarnations or symbols of gods and goddesses. Animals occupied a prominent place in ancient art across a number of civilisations and across a variety of media, including painting, pottery, and jewellery.',105,695,'GBP','Figurine, alabaster: a realistically carved South Arabian camel, depicted as a dromedary standing four-square with head erect.','Figurine, alabaster: a realistically carved South Arabian camel, identified as a dromedary, standing four-square with its head erect. The object is described as belonging to Ancient South Arabia, a geographical label for a region occupied by the kingdoms of Sabaʼ, Qatabān, Ma‘īn, Ḥaḍramawt, the Kingdom of Awsan, and the Himyarite Kingdom. The source notes that the territory of these kingdoms corresponds to parts of modern-day Yemen and Oman, extending north to the Arabian oasis of Dedan, to Ethiopia, and as far as the East African coast, including modern Tanzania. The text also states that animal depictions in this region had significance in religious rituals and as mythical creatures, as well as as incarnations or symbols of gods and goddesses.','https://www.antiquities.co.uk/shop/ancient-figurines-statues/camels/rare-south-arabian-alabaster-camel/','artandantiquities.co.uk'),(58,'0- _10_p007_57cd23fb','Dealer Contact Telephone +44 (0)208 364 4565 Mobile +44 (0)7833231322 Web antiquities.co.uk Email Contact Dealer Dealer Location The Gallery Trent Park Equestrian Centre Eastpole Farm House, Bramley Road Oakwood, N14 4UW, United Kingdom St James\'s Ancient Art 10 Charles II Street, Ground Floor St James London SW1Y 4AA View Map Object Description A South Arabian gold ring featuring a decorated, oval bezel. Date: Circa 2nd Century AD Dealer Location The Gallery Trent Park Equestrian Centre Eastpole Farm House, Bramley Road Oakwood, N14 4UW, United Kingdom St James\'s Ancient Art 10 Charles II Street, Ground Floor St James London SW1Y 4AA View Map Object Details dimensions W:1.6 x centimeters Dealer Opening Times By appointment only. South Arabian Gold Child’s Ring GBP 3,000.00 Contact Dealer To Purchase Object Description A South Arabian gold ring featuring a decorated, oval bezel. Date: Circa 2nd Century AD Object Literature Acquired 1970-1999. Comprised of a thick D-shaped hoop which flares outwards at the shoulders before widening to encompass the bezel. Incised lines have been used to create the particles of his hair, tied with a filet. To the left, from top to bottom, are the signs ‘nun’ (n) and ‘dal’ (d) respectively.',109,3000,'GBP','Ring, gold, South Arabian, with a decorated oval bezel, circa 2nd century AD. Width: 1.6 cm.','Ring, gold, South Arabian, with a decorated oval bezel, circa 2nd century AD. The ring is described as a child’s ring and is comprised of a thick D-shaped hoop which flares outwards at the shoulders before widening to encompass the bezel. Incised lines have been used to create the particles of his hair, tied with a filet. To the left, from top to bottom, are the signs ‘nun’ (n) and ‘dal’ (d) respectively. Width: 1.6 cm.','https://lapada.org/art-and-antiques/south-arabian-gold-childs-ring/','barakatgallery.com'),(59,'0- _10_p031_29d014fc','Promo tile carousel AUCTION SERIES | 2026 20th/21st Century Art worldwide AUCTION S