e top of its neck, the mouth slightly open revealing rows of teeth, the ears erect, the tails raised, the scene bordered above by a band of tongues 157/8 in. (40.3 cm) wide More from Antiquities View All View All',393,NULL,'','Relief, alabaster, Sabean, circa 1st century B.C.-1st century A.D. Carved in raised relief with a panel depicting two facing winged lions flanking a sprouting tree of life.','Relief, alabaster, Sabean, circa 1st century B.C.-1st century A.D. Carved in raised relief with a panel depicting two facing winged lions flanking a sprouting tree of life. Each lion has an arching wing, a leg resting on the tree, a mane rendered as a thin ridge along the top of the neck, a slightly open mouth showing rows of teeth, erect ears, and a raised tail. The scene is bordered above by a band of tongues. Width 15 7/8 in. (40.3 cm).','https://www.christies.com/lot/lot-1949521','christies.com'),(136,'0- _19_p011_4163a650','Skip to main content Home My Auctions Menu Search My Favourites Lot 321 CARVED SOAPSTONE FIGURE, YEMEN 1ST-2ND AD Belle Époque Auction: 20 March 2019 at 11:00 GMT £1,750 Description carved as a standing figure with arms outstretched, raised on a block base with incised script Dimensions 30cm high Footnote Note: Figures such as these are typical of South Arabia, where they were often placed in temples as votive offerings. Lot 321 CARVED SOAPSTONE FIGURE, YEMEN 1ST-2ND AD Belle Époque Auction: 20 March 2019 at 11:00 GMT £1,750 Description carved as a standing figure with arms outstretched, raised on a block base with incised script Dimensions 30cm high Footnote Note: Figures such as these are typical of South Arabia, where they were often placed in temples as votive offerings. CARVED SOAPSTONE FIGURE, YEMEN 1ST-2ND AD Belle Époque Auction: 20 March 2019 at 11:00 GMT £1,750 Description carved as a standing figure with arms outstretched, raised on a block base with incised script Dimensions 30cm high Footnote Note: Figures such as these are typical of South Arabia, where they were often placed in temples as votive offerings. They tended to be presented as donations, in the hope that the person gifting the figure would win favour with god. They also showed the wealth of the donor.',399,0,'GBP','Carved soapstone figure, Yemen, 1st-2nd AD, carved as a standing figure with arms outstretched, raised on a block base with incised script. Height 30 cm.','Carved soapstone figure, Yemen, 1st-2nd AD, carved as a standing figure with arms outstretched and raised on a block base with incised script. The figure is made of soapstone and is described as typical of South Arabia. It measures 30 cm high. The source notes that figures of this type were often placed in temples as votive offerings.','https://www.lyonandturnbull.com/auctions/belle-poque-567/lot/321','lyonandturnbull.com'),(137,'0- _19_p013_9c466c62','Ancient Figurines & Statues Greek Terracotta Seated Figure £ 1,150.00 Ancient Figurines & Statues Hellenistic Terracotta Female Head £ 295.00 Deities & Demi-Gods Roman Bronze Diana Figurine £ 1,300.00 Deities & Demi-Gods Roman Bronze Winged Cupid Figure £ 1,695.00 South Arabian Bronze Camel Rider £ 795.00 A very fine South Arabian bronze statuette of a dromedary and its rider. Ancient Figurines & Statues Greek Terracotta Seated Figure £ 1,150.00 Ancient Figurines & Statues Hellenistic Terracotta Female Head £ 295.00 Deities & Demi-Gods Roman Bronze Diana Figurine £ 1,300.00 Deities & Demi-Gods Roman Bronze Winged Cupid Figure £ 1,695.00 Ancient South Arabia is a geographical label referring to a region occupied by six semitic kingdoms: Sabaʼ, Qatabān, Ma‘īn, Ḥaḍramawt, the Kingdom of Awsan, and the Himyarite Kingdom. Additional information Culture Near Eastern Metal Copper Region Near East (Western Asiatic) Related products Ancient Appliqués & Protomes Roman Bronze Handle With Bacchants £ 1,200.00 Brooches & Dress Pins Pair of Greek Silver Brooches £ 450.00 Tomb Attendants & Offerings Han Dynasty Owl Statuette £ 2,950.00 Pouring Vessels Luristan Spouted Jar with Twisted Handle £ 795.00 Customers also bought Ancient Figurines & Statues Haasanlu Votive Bronze Sculpture of A Man Riding A Horse £ 750.00 you may also like... Home » All Antiquities » Ancient Figurines & Statues » Camel Figurines » South Arabian Bronze Camel Rider South Arabian Bronze Camel Rider £ 795.00 A very fine South Arabian bronze statuette of a dromedary and its rider. Out of stock Description Additional information Ancient South Arabia is a geographical label referring to a region occupied by six semitic kingdoms: Sabaʼ, Qatabān, Ma‘īn, Ḥaḍramawt, the Kingdom of Awsan, and the Himyarite Kingdom. The territory of these kingdoms corresponds to a modern-day area including Yemen, and extending into Oman, north to the Arabian oasis of Dedan, to Ethiopia, and even as far along as the East African Coast, into modern Tanzania. His arms are raised and what looks like crossed whilst holding onto a long cylindrical object, possibly part of a rein. Their depiction is thus endowed with significance in several contexts: in religious rituals, as mythical creatures, and as incarnations or symbols of gods and goddesses.',400,795,'GBP','Statuette, bronze, South Arabian, depicting a dromedary and rider. The rider’s arms are raised and crossed while holding a long cylindrical object, possibly part of a rein.','Statuette, bronze, South Arabian, of a dromedary and its rider. The rider is shown with raised, crossed arms holding a long cylindrical object, possibly part of a rein. The object is described as a very fine South Arabian bronze statuette. South Arabia is identified as a geographical label for a region occupied by the kingdoms of Sabaʼ, Qatabān, Ma‘īn, Ḥaḍramawt, Awsan, and the Himyarite Kingdom, corresponding to an area including modern-day Yemen and extending into Oman, north to the Arabian oasis of Dedan, to Ethiopia, and along the East African coast into modern Tanzania.','https://www.antiquities.co.uk/shop/ancient/pendant-bull-gold-arabian-jewellery/pendants/south','artandantiquities.co.uk'),(138,'0- _19_p014_2fe35087','Additional information Culture Ancient Greek Greek hellenistic rulers Alexander the Great Greek mythology Herakles, Zeus Metal Silver Region Near East (Western Asiatic), Southern Europe Related products Pouring Vessels Luristan Spouted Jar with Quadruped Handle £ 825.00 Hu Han Green-Glazed Vase with Relief Decoration £ 3,500.00 Ancient Appliqués & Protomes Medieval Gold Leaf Horse Appliqué Pair £ 650.00 Ancient Appliqués & Protomes Scythian Gold Mount £ 1,350.00 Customers also bought Drachm Selection of Alexander The Great Silver Drachms £ 195.00 Tetradrachm Ancient Greek Alexander the Great Silver Tetradrachm £ 750.00 Drachm Selection of Alexander the Great Silver Drachm Pendants £ 325.00 You may also like ..... Ancient Roman Coins Selection of City Commemorative Urbs Roma £ 55.00 Ancient Coins Silver Penny of King Henry III Selection £ 125.00 Ancient Coins Selection of Romano-Celtic Bronze Barbarous Radiates £ 25.00 Alexander the Great Silver Tetradrachm £ 1,570.00 Ancient Greek Alexander the Great Silver Tetradrachm £ 750.00 Rare Ancient Greek Alexander the Great Silver Tetradrachm £ 500.00 A very rare, posthumous Alexander the Great silver tetradrachm featuring the name and types of Alexander. Home » All Antiquities » Ancient Coins » Ancient Greek Coins » Tetradrachm » Rare Ancient Greek Alexander the Great Silver Tetradrachm Alexander the Great Silver Tetradrachm £ 1,570.00 Ancient Greek Alexander the Great Silver Tetradrachm £ 750.00 Rare Ancient Greek Alexander the Great Silver Tetradrachm £ 500.00 A very rare, posthumous Alexander the Great silver tetradrachm featuring the name and types of Alexander. Ancient Roman Coins Selection of City Commemorative Urbs Roma £ 55.00 Ancient Coins Silver Penny of King Henry III Selection £ 125.00 Ancient Coins Selection of Romano-Celtic Bronze Barbarous Radiates £ 25.00 The tetradrachm was Alexander’s silver stater, or standard denomination, with more of them minted than any other Alexander denomination. He wears the Nemean lion-skin headdress, one of Herakles typical attributes, which imbues the Greek ruler with divine qualities. The Greek inscription ΑΛΕΞΑΝ∆ΡΟΥ is written vertically to the right of the figure of Zeus. Unlike Alexander’s bronze coinage, which was largely used in local marketplaces, tetradrachm were international, imperial coins that were used in state transactions. The reverse of the coin depicts the Greek god Zeus, seated to the left on a throne, holding an eagle in his right hand and sceptre in his left.',401,500,'£','Coin, silver. Ancient Greek posthumous tetradrachm of Alexander the Great, featuring the name and types of Alexander. The obverse shows Alexander wearing the Nemean lion-skin headdress associated with Herakles; the reverse depicts Zeus seated left on a throne, holding an eagle and sceptre, with the inscription ΑΛΕΞΑΝΔΡΟΥ.','Coin, silver. Ancient Greek posthumous tetradrachm of Alexander the Great, attributed to the Hellenistic period and associated with the Near East (Western Asiatic) and Southern Europe. The tetradrachm was Alexander’s silver stater, or standard denomination, and was minted in greater numbers than any other Alexander denomination. The obverse depicts Alexander wearing the Nemean lion-skin headdress, one of Herakles’ typical attributes, and the reverse shows the Greek god Zeus seated to the left on a throne, holding an eagle in his right hand and a sceptre in his left. The Greek inscription ΑΛΕΞΑΝ∆ΡΟΥ is written vertically to the right of the figure of Zeus. The text describes the coin as a very rare, posthumous Alexander the Great silver tetradrachm featuring the name and types of Alexander.','https://www.antiquities.co.uk/shop/ancient-figurines/camel-alabaster-arabian-south-statues/camels/rare','artandantiquities.co.uk'),(139,'0- _19_p020_651730f0','Ancient Egyptian Shabti- Ancient Egyptian Amulets - Ancient Egyptian Pottery - Ancie