-e sultan al-anbiya \'ala sakinuha afzal al-thanaya waqafahu al-\'abd al-muhtaj usta ibrahim sar-i [sic] qazghaniyan bandheh-ye Sultan Suleyman Khan tarikh-e sana 945 fi awasit dhu\'l hijja dha\'lhajj (sic) [Dhi\'l-hajjah] ghafara allah lahu ‘Endowment to the tomb of His Holiness the Sultan of Prophets, may there be the best of praises upon its resident. inscriptions waqf-e rawzeh-ye hazrat-e sultan al-anbiya \'ala sakinuha afzal al-thanaya waqafahu al-\'abd al-muhtaj usta ibrahim sar-i [sic] qazghaniyan bandheh-ye Sultan Suleyman Khan tarikh-e sana 945 fi awasit dhu\'l hijja dha\'lhajj (sic) [Dhi\'l-hajjah] ghafara allah lahu ‘Endowment to the tomb of His Holiness the Sultan of Prophets, may there be the best of praises upon its resident. The needy servant (of God) Usta Ibrahim the head cauldron maker, the servant of Sultan Suleyman Khan endowed it in the year 945 in the middle of Dhu’l-Hijja (May 1539), may God have mercy on him.’ This impressive tombak candlestick is a pair to a candlestick in the David Collection, Copenhagen (inv. The inscription states that the candlestick was endowed by Usta Ibrahim, the head cauldron maker in the service of Suleyman the Magnificent, donated to the \"tomb of the sultan of all prophets\" in Dhu’l-Hijjah 945 AH/May 1539 AD. The elegant, thuluth inscription bears the name of Suleyman the Magnificent, endowed by a certain Usta Ibrahim in his service to the “tomb of His Holiness the Sultan of Prophets.” This most likely refers to the Prophet Muhammad and thus its donation to the Prophet’s Mosque, Medina. Selim I consolidated the Ottoman expansion, incorporating Syria, Palestine, Egypt and the Hijaz into his empire and becoming guardian of the holy sites of Mecca, Medina and Jerusalem.',485,NULL,'','Candlestick, gilt-copper (tombak), Ottoman, Turkey, dated Dhu\'l-Hijja 945 AH/May 1539 AD. The large truncated conical body is surmounted by a flat drip tray, with a tall ridged cylindrical neck and tapered ridged candle holder; the base of the body bears a finely engraved thuluth inscription.','Candlestick, gilt-copper (tombak), Ottoman, Turkey, dated Dhu\'l-Hijja 945 AH/May 1539 AD. The object has a large truncated conical body surmounted by a flat drip tray, a tall ridged cylindrical neck, and a tapered ridged candle holder. The base of the body is engraved with a thuluth inscription recording the endowment of the candlestick by Usta Ibrahim, described as the head cauldron maker and servant of Sultan Suleyman Khan, to the \"tomb of His Holiness the Sultan of Prophets.\" The inscription gives the date as the middle of Dhu\'l-Hijja 945 AH, corresponding to May 1539 AD. The text identifies the object as an Ottoman courtly metalwork piece associated with Suleyman the Magnificent.','https://www.sothebys.com/en/buy/auction/2024/arts-of-the-islamic-world-and-india/a-large-gilt-copper-tombak-candlestick','sothebys.com'),(155,'0- _21_p012_cb36e5e4','Skip to main content Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Figure of a Female Worshiper Thumbnail Figure of a Female Worshiper Thumbnail Figure of a Female Worshiper South Arabian (Sculptor) 2nd century BCE-1st century CE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) The variety of statuettes within the body of South Arabian sculpture is relatively small ,  Giraud and Carolyn Foster, Baltimore, between 1963 and 1971, by purchase',495,NULL,'','Figure of a female worshiper, calcite-alabaster, South Arabian, dated to the 2nd century BCE–1st century CE.','Figure of a female worshiper, calcite-alabaster, South Arabian sculpture, dated to the 2nd century BCE–1st century CE. The object is identified as a statuette within the corpus of South Arabian sculpture, which is described as relatively small in variety. The source text provides no further technical or contextual details beyond the material, cultural attribution, and date.','https://art.thewalters.org/detail/76488/figure-of-a-female-worshiper/','art.thewalters.org'),(156,'0- _21_p013_5466316d','Skip to main content Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Trapezoidal Stela with a Concave Top Thumbnail Trapezoidal Stela with a Concave Top South Arabian (Sculptor) mid 2nd century CE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) The stela is inserted into a separate base. Notify the curator Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Trapezoidal Stela with a Concave Top Thumbnail Trapezoidal Stela with a Concave Top South Arabian (Sculptor) mid 2nd century CE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) The stela is inserted into a separate base. Inscription [Transliteration] Qsdm / grbm [Translation] Qesdem of the Gherbem clan Provenance Provenance (from the French provenir , \'to come from/forth\') is the chronology of the ownership, custody, or location of a historical object. Notify the curator Trapezoidal Stela with a Concave Top South Arabian (Sculptor) mid 2nd century CE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) The stela is inserted into a separate base. (15 x 10 x 8.4 cm) Credit Line Gift of Giraud and Carolyn Foster, 2007 Location in Museum Not on view Accession Number In libraries, galleries, museums, and archives, an accession number is a unique identifier assigned to each object in the collection. Conservation Date Description Narrative 5/4/2008 Treatment cleaned social-item social-item social-item Geographies Arabian Peninsula (Place of Origin) Measurements H: 5 7/8 x W: 3 15/16 x D: 3 5/16 in. Sotheby\'s, London, between 1963 and 1971',496,NULL,'','Stela, calcite-alabaster, South Arabian, mid 2nd century CE. Trapezoidal stela with a concave top, inserted into a separate base, inscribed with the transliteration Qsdm / grbm.','Stela, calcite-alabaster, South Arabian, mid 2nd century CE. Trapezoidal stela with a concave top, inserted into a separate base. The object is made of calcite-alabaster from South Arabia and measures 15 x 10 x 8.4 cm (H: 5 7/8 x W: 3 15/16 x D: 3 5/16 in.). It bears an inscription transliterated as Qsdm / grbm, translated as Qesdem of the Gherbem clan. The recorded provenance notes Sotheby\'s, London, between 1963 and 1971. The object was cleaned on 5/4/2008.','https://art.thewalters.org/detail/76515/trapezoidal-stela-with-a-concave-top/#item-modal','art.thewalters.org'),(157,'0- _21_p014_587c3579','Skip to main content Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb South Arabian (Sculptor) 1st century CE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) Sculpted stone heads, mounted on bases and placed in the vestibules of burial chambers, were common in the cemetery of Timna\', capital of the kingdom of Qataban. Notify the curator Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb Thumbnail Head of Lady Helqeb South Arabian (Sculptor) 1st century CE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) Sculpted stone heads, mounted on bases and placed in the vestibules of burial chambers, were common in the cemetery of Timna\', capital of the kingdom of Qataban. Notify the curator Head of Lady Helqeb South Arabian (Sculptor) 1st century CE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) Sculpted stone heads, mounted on bases and placed in the vestibules of burial chambers, were common in the cemetery of Timna\', capital of the kingdom of Qataban. (24 x 11 x 7 cm) Credit Line Gift of Giraud and Carolyn Foster, 2007 Location in Museum Centre Street: Second Floor: Ancient Near Eastern Art Accession Number In libraries, galleries, museums, and archives, an accession number is a unique identifier assigned to each object in the collection. Inscription [Transliteration] On base: Hlqb Dt / Wqs Provenance Provenance (from the French provenir , \'to come from/forth\') is the chronology of the ownership, custody, or location of a historical object. Conservation Date Description Narrative 5/1/2008 Treatment cleaned social-item social-item social-item Geographies Arabian Peninsula (Place of Origin) Measurements H: 9 7/16 x W: 4 5/16 x D: 2 3/4 in. Sotheby\'s, London, between 1963 and 1971',497,NULL,'','Head of Lady Helqeb, calcite-alabaster, South Arabian sculpture, 1st century CE. Sculpted stone head mounted on a base, from South Arabia; inscription on base: Hlqb Dt / Wqs.','Head of Lady Helqeb, calcite-alabaster, South Arabian sculpture, 1st century CE. Sculpted stone head from South Arabia, carved in calcite-alabaster and mounted on a base. The object measures 24 x 11 x 7 cm (H: 9 7/16 x W: 4 5/16 x D: 2 3/4 in.). An inscription on the base reads: Hlqb Dt / Wqs. The source text notes that sculpted stone heads mounted on bases and placed in the vestibules of burial chambers were common in the cemetery of Timna\', capital of the kingdom of Qataban.','https://art.thewalters.org/detail/76493/head-of-lady-helqeb/','art.thewalters.org'),(158,'0- _21_p015_8de652d6','Skip to main content Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Stela with a Bull\'s Head Thumbnail Stela with a Bull\'s Head South Arabian (Sculptor) 3rd century BCE-1st century CE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) This stela with an unusual raised band-like frame was probably not inserted in a base but placed in a wall niche in a tomb. Notify the curator Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Stela with a Bull\'s Head Thumbnail Stela with a Bull\'s Head South Arabian (Sculptor) 3rd century BCE-1st century CE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) This stela with an unusual raised band-like frame was probably not inserted in a base but placed in a wall niche in a tomb. Notify the curator Stela with a Bull\'s Head South Arabian (Sculptor) 3rd century BCE-1st century CE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) This stela with an unusual raised band-like frame was probably not inserted in a base but placed in a wall niche in a tomb. Inscription [Transliteration] \'rsm (or) \'rst [Translation] \'Resem (or) \'Reset Provenance Provenance (from the French provenir , \'to come from/forth\') is the chronology of the ownership, custody, or location of a historical object. (17.3 x 9.7 x 4 cm) Credit Line Gift of Giraud and Carolyn Foster, 2007 Location in Museum Not on view Accession Number In libraries, galleries, museums, and archives, an accession number is a unique identifier assigned to each object in the collection. Conservation Date Description Narrative 5/8/2008 Treatment cleaned social-item social-item social-item Geographies Arabian Peninsula (Place of Origin) Measurements H: 6 13/16 x W: 3 13/16 x D: 1 9/16 in. The bull\'s image is executed in raised relief',498,NULL,'','Stela, calcite-alabaster, South Arabian, 3rd century BCE-1st century CE. The stela has an unusual raised band-like frame and a bull\'s head in raised relief.','Stela, calcite-alabaster, South Arabian, 3rd century BCE-1st century CE. This stela is carved in calcite-alabaster and features an unusual raised band-like frame. The bull\'s image is executed in raised relief. It was probably not inserted in a base but placed in a wall niche in a tomb. An inscription is present, transliterated as \'rsm (or) \'rst and translated as \'Resem (or) \'Reset. The recorded measurements are H: 6 13/16 x W: 3 13/16 x D: 1 9/16 in. (17.3 x 9.7 x 4 cm).','https://art.thewalters.org/detail/76480/stela-with-a-bulls-head/','art.thewalters.org'),(159,'0- _21_p016_7c432e20','Skip to main content Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Stela with a Seated Woman Thumbnail Stela with a Seated Woman Thumbnail Stela with a Seated Woman Thumbnail Stela with a Seated Woman South Arabian (Sculptor) 2nd-1st century BCE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) This woman is seated on a folding stool with a cushioned seat. Notify the curator Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Stela with a Seated Woman Thumbnail Stela with a Seated Woman Thumbnail Stela with a Seated Woman Thumbnail Stela with a Seated Woman South Arabian (Sculptor) 2nd-1st century BCE calcite-alabaster (South Arabia) This woman is seated on a folding stool with a cushioned seat. Inscription [Transliteration] Hywt /Dmrn',499,NULL,'','Stela, calcite-alabaster, South Arabian, 2nd-1st century BCE. The stela depicts a seated woman on a folding stool with a cushioned seat.','Stela, calcite-alabaster, South Arabian, 2nd-1st century BCE. The object depicts a woman seated on a folding stool with a cushioned seat. An inscription is present, transliterated as Hywt /Dmrn. The material is identified as calcite-alabaster from South Arabia.','https://art.thewalters.org/detail/76487/stela-with-a-seated-woman/','art.thewalters.org'),(160,'0- _21_p019_6a294d81','تاجر فرنسي يبيع أثراً يمنياً مهرباً في مزاد مونت كارلو تاجر فرنسي يبيع أثراً يمنياً مهرباً في مزاد مونت كارلو ..اخبار اليمن يمن ايكو - 2024-10-27 | 160 قراءة - الأكثر زيارة',502,NULL,'','','','https://sa24.co/show770963277.html','sa24.co '),(161,'0- _21_p026_e8ab5e07','Skip to main content Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Pendant with Human Face Thumbnail Pendant with Human Face South Arabian (Sculptor) 1st-5th century CE iron (South Arabia) The oval plaque features a male head wearing an elaborate headdress that resembles the Macedonian \"kausia\" (a kind of flat hat). Notify the curator Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Pendant with Human Face Thumbnail Pendant with Human Face South Arabian (Sculptor) 1st-5th century CE iron (South Arabia) The oval plaque features a male head wearing an elaborate headdress that resembles the Macedonian \"kausia\" (a kind of flat hat). Notify the curator Pendant with Human Face South Arabian (Sculptor) 1st-5th century CE iron (South Arabia) The oval plaque features a male head wearing an elaborate headdress that resembles the Macedonian \"kausia\" (a kind of flat hat). (6.8 x 4 x 2.5 cm) Credit Line Gift of Giraud and Carolyn Foster, 2007 Location in Museum Not on view Accession Number In libraries, galleries, museums, and archives, an accession number is a unique identifier assigned to each object in the collection. Provenance Provenance (from the French provenir , \'to come from/forth\') is the chronology of the ownership, custody, or location of a historical object. Similar pendants were made in the Roman Empire, but it is impossible to determine whether this pendant reached South Arabia as an import or was made locally after a foreign model. Ahmed [local art dealer], Ta\'izz, Yemen',509,NULL,'','Pendant with human face, iron, South Arabian, 1st-5th century CE. The oval plaque features a male head wearing an elaborate headdress resembling the Macedonian kausia.','Pendant with human face, iron, South Arabian, 1st-5th century CE. The object is an oval plaque depicting a male head with an elaborate headdress resembling the Macedonian kausia, a flat hat. The pendant is dated broadly to the 1st-5th century CE and is attributed to South Arabia. Similar pendants were made in the Roman Empire, but it is not possible to determine from the source whether this example reached South Arabia as an import or was made locally after a foreign model. The recorded dimensions are 6.8 x 4 x 2.5 cm.','https://art.thewalters.org/detail/76495/pendant-with-human-face/','art.thewalters.org'),(162,'0- _21_p031_bcd0f28f','Press Property from the Esteemed Ernest and Ella Brummer Collection Quadruples Estimate Selling for More than $2 Million December 08, 2023 December 07, 2023 Important Kashmir Unheated Sapphire and Diamond Ring Sells for $1.29M October 19, 2023 Time & Space: Watches From the Collection of Glen De Vries, the Inaugural Auction of Hindman’s New York Saleroom, Achieves a Total Surpassing $3 Million September 21, 2023 Hindman Names Reginald Brack Senior Vice President, Director of Jewelry & Watches June 07, 2023 A Classical Collection: Property From The Estate Of Former Chicago Symphony Orchestra Violinist Fred Spector To Be Auctioned At Hindman June 07, 2023 Property From a David Collins-Designed New York Residence to be Presented At Hindman June 06, 2023 Hindman New York Appoints Leslie Roskind Senior Specialist, Jewelry & Watches June 05, 2023 Karl Lagerfeld for Chloé \"Shower Dress” to Anchor Hindman Summer Fashion Auction May 18, 2023 First Edition Jane Austen Novels Soar Past Estimates at Hindman May 18, 2023 Cartier, Art Deco, Jade, Diamond and