A.D.',514,NULL,'','Object type and main material are not explicitly identified in the source text. The text refers to a Roman marble head of a youth wearing a laurel wreath, sold for $504,000 against an estimate of $40,000 to $60,000.','Object type and main material are not explicitly identified in the source text. The available description identifies the object as a Roman marble head of a youth wearing a laurel wreath, dated to the Roman period and sold for $504,000 against an estimate of $40,000 to $60,000. No further technical details, dimensions, or condition information are provided in the source text.','https://hindmanauctions.com/new-noteworthy/property-from-the-esteemed-ernest-and-ella-brummer-collection-quadruples-estimate-selling-for-more-than-2-million','hindmanauctions.com'),(163,'0- _28_p001_aeebab61','Object Name Plakette Culture Südarabisch Location of discovery: Südarabien Material/technology: Bronze Dimensions: H 7,4 cm, B 8,5 cm, T 0,9 cm',515,NULL,'','Plaquette, bronze, South Arabian. H 7.4 cm, W 8.5 cm, D 0.9 cm.','Plaquette, bronze, South Arabian. The object is made of bronze and is recorded with dimensions of H 7.4 cm, W 8.5 cm, and D 0.9 cm. The place of discovery is South Arabia.','https://www.khm.at/en/artworks/mann-zu-zwei-loewen-376268/','khm.at'),(164,'0- _28_p002_c27fb803','(?) Objektbezeichnung Beschlag Kultur Südarabisch Fundort: Südarabien Material/Technik: Bronze Maße: H 5,1 cm, B 4,2 cm, T 0,25 cm, G 24,12 g Bildrecht Kunsthistorisches Museum, Ägyptisch - Orientalische Sammlung Inv. Nutzungsbedingungen & AGBs Für eine Veröffentlichung (wissenschaftlich oder kommerziell) schicken Sie uns bitte eine Reproduktionsanfrage Datei herunterladen arrow_outward Mann mit zwei Steinböcken 4.-2. Objekt speichern Sie können die Abbildung für den privaten Gebrauch herunterladen und nutzen. Ägyptische Sammlung, SEM 141 Provenienz 1894 aus der Sammlung Glaser übernommen',516,NULL,'','Object, bronze. South Arabian fitting from South Arabia, measuring H 5.1 cm, W 4.2 cm, D 0.25 cm, and weighing 24.12 g. Provenance: acquired in 1894 from the Glaser collection.','Object, bronze. South Arabian fitting from South Arabia. The object is recorded as a fitting (Beschlag) and is made of bronze. Its dimensions are H 5.1 cm, W 4.2 cm, D 0.25 cm, with a weight of 24.12 g. The record notes provenance as having been taken over in 1894 from the Glaser collection. The source also includes the inventory reference SEM 141 and identifies the holding as the Egyptian Collection, but no further typological or chronological details are provided.','https://www.khm.at/kunstwerke/mann-mit-zwei-steinböecken-376277','khm.at'),(165,'0- _28_p004_558dd6e7','Objektbezeichnung Lampe Kultur Südarabisch Fundort: Schabwa (Jemen) Material/Technik: Bronze Maße: H 34 cm, L 25,5 cm, B 11 cm Bildrecht Kunsthistorisches Museum, Ägyptisch - Orientalische Sammlung Inv. location_on zu sehen: Kunsthistorisches Museum , Ägyptisch-Orientalische Sammlung Saal VIa Die Lampe besteht aus einer länglichen Ölwanne und einem gekrümmten Bügel, der aus der Rückwand der Ölwanne herausragt und mit dem Vorderteil eines springenen Steinbockes geschmückt ist. Nutzungsbedingungen & AGBs Für eine Veröffentlichung (wissenschaftlich oder kommerziell) schicken Sie uns bitte eine Reproduktionsanfrage Datei herunterladen arrow_outward Objekt speichern Sie können die Abbildung für den privaten Gebrauch herunterladen und nutzen. Nutzungsbedingungen & AGBs Für eine Veröffentlichung (wissenschaftlich oder kommerziell) schicken Sie uns bitte eine Reproduktionsanfrage Datei herunterladen arrow_outward Lampe mit Steinbockprotom Vermutlich 1.-3. chevron_left chevron_right Die Lampe besteht aus einer länglichen Ölwanne und einem gekrümmten Bügel, der aus der Rückwand der Ölwanne herausragt und mit dem Vorderteil eines springenen Steinbockes geschmückt ist. Der Steinbock ist in der altsüdarabischen Ikonographie ein wichtiges Motiv, da er als Symbol des Mondgottes galt. Ägyptische Sammlung, SEM 694 Provenienz 1900 Ankauf aus der Südarabien-Expedition 1898-1899 von D.H. Objekt speichern Sie können die Abbildung für den privaten Gebrauch herunterladen und nutzen.',518,NULL,'','Lamp, bronze, South Arabian, probably 1st-3rd century. The lamp has an elongated oil reservoir and a curved handle rising from the back wall, decorated with the forepart of a leaping ibex.','Lamp, bronze, South Arabian, probably 1st-3rd century. The object consists of an elongated oil reservoir and a curved handle projecting from the back wall of the reservoir. The handle is decorated with the forepart of a leaping ibex. The ibex is a significant motif in ancient South Arabian iconography, where it was associated with the moon god. Dimensions: H. 34 cm, L. 25.5 cm, W. 11 cm. Findspot: Shabwa, Yemen. Provenance: acquired in 1900 from the South Arabia expedition of 1898-1899.','https://www.khm.at/kunstwerke/lampe-mit-steinbockprotom-376564','khm.at'),(166,'0- _28_p005_0ecce4f0','(?) Objektbezeichnung Votivgabe Kultur Südarabisch Fundort: Südarabien Material/Technik: Bronze Maße: H 2,5 cm, B 6,6 cm, T 1,7 cm Bildrecht Kunsthistorisches Museum, Ägyptisch - Orientalische Sammlung Inv. Nutzungsbedingungen & AGBs Für eine Veröffentlichung (wissenschaftlich oder kommerziell) schicken Sie uns bitte eine Reproduktionsanfrage Datei herunterladen arrow_outward Statuette einer Maus 1. Nutzungsbedingungen & AGBs Für eine Veröffentlichung (wissenschaftlich oder kommerziell) schicken Sie uns bitte eine Reproduktionsanfrage Datei herunterladen arrow_outward Objekt speichern Sie können die Abbildung für den privaten Gebrauch herunterladen und nutzen. (?) location_on zu sehen: Kunsthistorisches Museum , Ägyptisch-Orientalische Sammlung Saal VIa chevron_left chevron_right Zeit: 1. Objekt speichern Sie können die Abbildung für den privaten Gebrauch herunterladen und nutzen. Ägyptische Sammlung, SEM 135 Provenienz 1894 aus der Sammlung Glaser übernommen',519,NULL,'','Votive offering, bronze, from South Arabia. Statuette of a mouse, measuring H 2.5 cm, W 6.6 cm, D 1.7 cm.','Votive offering, bronze, from South Arabia. Statuette of a mouse, recorded as a South Arabian object and described as a votive gift. The object measures 2.5 cm in height, 6.6 cm in width, and 1.7 cm in depth. Provenance note: acquired from the Glaser collection in 1894.','https://www.khm.at/kunstwerke/statuette-maus-einer-376270','khm.at'),(167,'0- _28_p006_b6ac7e93','Objektbezeichnung Relief Kultur Südarabisch Fundort: Südarabien Material/Technik: Kalkstein Maße: H 30 cm, B 45,5 cm, T 8,6 - 9,7 cm, G 25,1 kg Bildrecht Kunsthistorisches Museum, Ägyptisch - Orientalische Sammlung Inv. Nutzungsbedingungen & AGBs Für eine Veröffentlichung (wissenschaftlich oder kommerziell) schicken Sie uns bitte eine Reproduktionsanfrage Datei herunterladen arrow_outward Relief eines Mannes mit Schnurrbart und Haarkranz Um 500 n. Ägyptische Sammlung, SEM 692 Provenienz 1900 Ankauf aus der Südarabien-Expedition 1898-1899 von D.H. Objekt speichern Sie können die Abbildung für den privaten Gebrauch herunterladen und nutzen.',520,NULL,'','Relief, limestone, South Arabian culture, from South Arabia. The relief depicts a man with a moustache and a hair wreath. It dates to around 500 CE and is in the Egyptian Collection, inv. SEM 692.','Relief, limestone, South Arabian culture, from South Arabia. The object measures H 30 cm, W 45.5 cm, D 8.6–9.7 cm, and weighs 25.1 kg. It depicts a man with a moustache and a hair wreath. The relief is dated to around 500 CE and is recorded in the Egyptian Collection under inv. SEM 692. Provenance note: acquired in 1900 from the South Arabia expedition of 1898–1899.','https://www.khm.at/kunstwerke/relief-mit-haarkranz-eines-mannes-mit-schnurrbart-376562','khm.at'),(168,'0- _28_p007_7f5ed1e5','Objektbezeichnung Inschrift Kultur Südarabisch Fundort: Riyam Material/Technik: Kalkstein Maße: H 79 cm, B 48 cm, T 13 cm Bildrecht Kunsthistorisches Museum, Ägyptisch - Orientalische Sammlung Inv. Nutzungsbedingungen & AGBs Für eine Veröffentlichung (wissenschaftlich oder kommerziell) schicken Sie uns bitte eine Reproduktionsanfrage Datei herunterladen arrow_outward Vertragsstele von Riyâm Anfang 3. location_on zu sehen: Kunsthistorisches Museum , Ägyptisch-Orientalische Sammlung Saal VIa Zeit: Anfang 3. Objekt speichern Sie können die Abbildung für den privaten Gebrauch herunterladen und nutzen. Ägyptische Sammlung, SEM 1 Provenienz 1894 aus der Sammlung Glaser übernommen',521,NULL,'','Inscription, South Arabian, limestone, from Riyam. The object measures H 79 cm, W 48 cm, D 13 cm and dates to the early 3rd century.','Inscription, limestone, South Arabian, from Riyam. This contractual stele is made of limestone and measures H 79 cm, W 48 cm, D 13 cm. It is dated to the early 3rd century. The provenance note states that it was acquired in 1894 from the Glaser collection.','https://www.khm.at/kunstwerke/vertragsstele-riy-m-375971','khm.at'),(169,'0- _28_p008_fefb8c59','Objektbezeichnung Dachrinne Kultur Südarabisch Fundort: Südarabien Material/Technik: Kalkstein Maße: H 6 cm, B 22,5 cm, T 47,2 cm Bildrecht Kunsthistorisches Museum, Ägyptisch - Orientalische Sammlung Inv. Nutzungsbedingungen & AGBs Für eine Veröffentlichung (wissenschaftlich oder kommerziell) schicken Sie uns bitte eine Reproduktionsanfrage Datei herunterladen arrow_outward Regenrinne mit Stierkopf 1.-3. location_on zu sehen: Kunsthistorisches Museum , Ägyptisch-Orientalische Sammlung Saal VIa Zeit: 1.-3. Objekt speichern Sie können die Abbildung für den privaten Gebrauch herunterladen und nutzen. Ägyptische Sammlung, SEM 124 Provenienz 1894 aus der Sammlung Glaser übernommen',522,NULL,'','Dachrinne, Kalkstein, südarabisch, aus Südarabien. Maße: H 6 cm, B 22,5 cm, T 47,2 cm. Zeit: 1.–3. Jahrhundert.','Dachrinne, Kalkstein, südarabisch, aus Südarabien. Die Regenrinne ist mit einem Stierkopf versehen. Maße: H 6 cm, B 22,5 cm, T 47,2 cm. Datierung: 1.–3. Jahrhundert. Provenienz: 1894 aus der Sammlung Glaser übernommen.','https://www.khm.at/kunstwerke/regenrinne-stierkopf-mit-376217','khm.at'),(170,'0- _28_p010_29618710','Ultimately, this is a placeholder solution so that more time can be spent on fingerprinting and identifying headless browsers (EG: via how they do font rendering) so that the challenge proof of work page doesn\'t need to be presented to users that are much more likely to be legitimate. You are seeing this because the administrator of this website has set up Anubis to protect the server against the scourge of AI companies aggressively scraping websites. The idea is that at individual scales the additional load is ignorable, but at mass scraper levels it adds up and makes scraping much more expensive. Anubis uses a Proof-of-Work scheme in the vein of Hashcash, a proposed proof-of-work scheme for reducing email spam. Please note that Anubis requires the use of modern JavaScript features that plugins like JShelter will disable. This can and does cause downtime for the websites, which makes their resources inaccessible for everyone. Please disable JShelter or other such plugins for this domain.',524,NULL,'','Placeholder solution using Anubis proof-of-work to protect a website from aggressive scraping and to reduce the need to present challenge pages to likely legitimate users.','Placeholder solution using Anubis proof-of-work to protect a server against aggressive scraping by AI companies. The system is described as a temporary measure intended to allow more time for fingerprinting and identifying headless browsers, for example through font rendering behavior, so that challenge proof-of-work pages do not need to be shown to users more likely to be legitimate. It uses a Proof-of-Work scheme in the vein of Hashcash, a proposed proof-of-work method for reducing email spam. The text notes that Anubis requires modern JavaScript features and that plugins such as JShelter may disable them, which can cause downtime and make website resources inaccessible to all users.','https://dasi.cnr.it/index.php?id=30&prjId=1&corId=0&colId=0&navId=336800338&recId=7704&mark=07704%2C001%2C001','dasi.cnr.it'),(171,'0- _28_p012_b3929ea9','Ultimately, this is a placeholder solution so that more time can be spent on fingerprinting and identifying headless browsers (EG: via how they do font rendering) so that the challenge proof of work page doesn\'t need to be presented to users that are much more likely to be legitimate. You are seeing this because the administrator of this website has set up Anubis to protect the server against the scourge of AI companies aggressively scraping websites. The idea is that at individual scales the additional load is ignorable, but at mass scraper levels it adds up and makes scraping much more expensive. Anubis uses a Proof-of-Work scheme in the vein of Hashcash, a proposed proof-of-work scheme for reducing email spam. Please note that Anubis requires the use of modern JavaScript features that plugins like JShelter will disable. This can and does cause downtime for the websites, which makes their resources inaccessible for everyone. Please disable JShelter or other such plugins for this domain.',526,NULL,'','No object is described in the source text; the text concerns Anubis, a proof-of-work protection system for websites.','No archaeological object, material, typology, dimensions, period, or manufacturing technique is described in the source text. The text instead explains that Anubis is used as a placeholder solution to protect a server against aggressive scraping, employing a proof-of-work scheme in the vein of Hashcash. It also notes that the system relies on modern JavaScript features and may be affected by plugins such as JShelter, which can cause downtime and restrict access to website resources.','https://dasi.cnr.it/index.php?id=30&prjId=1&corId=0&colId=0&navId=24979542&recId=3795&mark=03795%2C001%2C002','dasi.cnr.it'),(172,'0- _28_p021_0c783b35','Ultimately, this is a placeholder solution so that more time can be spent on fingerprinting and identifying headless browsers (EG: via how they do font rendering) so that the challenge proof of work page doesn\'t need to be presented to users that are much more likely to be legitimate. You are seeing this because the administrator of this website has set up Anubis to protect the server against the scourge of AI companies aggressively scraping websites. The idea is that at individual scales the additional load is ignorable, but at mass scraper levels it adds up and makes scraping much more expensive. Anubis uses a Proof-of-Work scheme in the vein of Hashcash, a proposed proof-of-work scheme for reducing email spam. Please note that Anubis requires the use of modern JavaScript features that plugins like JShelter will disable. This can and does cause downtime for the websites, which makes their resources inaccessible for everyone. Please disable JShelter or other such plugins for this domain.',535,NULL,'','Placeholder solution using Anubis proof-of-work to protect a website from aggressive scraping and to reduce the need to present challenge pages to likely legitimate users.','Placeholder solution using Anubis proof-of-work to protect a website against aggressive scraping by AI companies. The system is described as a temporary measure intended to allow more time for fingerprinting and identifying headless browsers, for example through font rendering behavior, so that challenge proof-of-work pages do not need to be shown to users more likely to be legitimate. Anubis uses a proof-of-work scheme in the vein of Hashcash, a proposed proof-of-work method for reducing email spam. The text notes that the system requires modern JavaScript features and that plugins such as JShelter may disable them, which can cause downtime and make website resources inaccessible to all users.','https://dasi.cnr.it/index.php?id=30&prjId=1&corId=0&colId=0&navId=920737773&recId=9384&mark=09384%2C001%2C004','dasi.cnr.it'),(173,'0- _28_p027_49196eb4','J.-C, Salle 314 - Arabie, Cimaise Index Mode d\'acquisition achat Name relief Materials albâtre Techniques bas-relief champlevé Description/Features oiseau - grappe de raisin Places Yémen Calvet, Yves ',541,NULL,'','Relief in alabaster, carved in bas-relief and champlevé, depicting a bird and a bunch of grapes. Provenance: Yemen.','Relief in alabaster, executed in bas-relief and champlevé, with a decorative motif of a bird and a bunch of grapes. The object is recorded as coming from Yemen. Acquisition mode: purchase. The source text also mentions Yves Calvet.','https://collections.louvre.fr/en/ark:/53355/cl010166659','collections.louvre.fr'),(174,'0- _28_p028_76ccf6a0','Bardey, Pierre Acquisition details don Acquisition date date de comité/commission : 12/12/1912 date du conseil : 13/01/1913 Owned by Etat Held by Musée du Louvre, Département des Antiquités orientales Location of object Current location Marseille (France), Musée d\'Archéologie Méditerranéenne - Centre de la Vieille Charité Index Mode d\'acquisition don Name figurine Materials bronze Description/Features cheval - enfant - cavalier Places Yémen Ali Aqil, Azza ',542,NULL,'','Figurine, bronze, depicting a horse with a child rider. The object was acquired by donation and is held by the Musée du Louvre, Département des Antiquités orientales; current location: Musée d\'Archéologie Méditerranéenne - Centre de la Vieille Charité, Marseille, France.','Figurine, bronze, depicting a horse, a child, and a rider. The object was acquired by donation (don), with committee/commission date 12/12/1912 and council date 13/01/1913. It is owned by the State and held by the Musée du Louvre, Département des Antiquités orientales. The current location is Marseille (France), Musée d\'Archéologie Méditerranéenne - Centre de la Vieille Charité. The place of origin is given as Yemen, Ali Aqil, Azza.','https://collections.louvre.fr/en/ark:/53355/cl010167149','collections.louvre.fr'),(175,'0- _28_p029_e567a978','Bardey, Pierre Acquisition details don Acquisition date date de comité/commission : 12/12/1912 date du conseil : 13/01/1913 Owned by Etat Held by Musée du Louvre, Département des Antiquités orientales Location of object Current location Marseille (France), Musée d\'Archéologie Méditerranéenne - Centre de la Vieille Charité Index Mode d\'acquisition don Name figurine Materials bronze Description/Features cheval - enfant - cavalier Places Yémen Ali Aqil, Azza ',543,NULL,'','Figurine, bronze, depicting a horse, child, and rider. Acquired by donation and held by the Musée du Louvre, Département des Antiquités orientales; current location Marseille, Musée d\'Archéologie Méditerranéenne - Centre de la Vieille Charité.','Figurine, bronze. The object is described as a figurine with the features horse, child, and rider. It was acquired by donation (don) and is owned by the State, held by the Musée du Louvre, Département des Antiquités orientales. The current location is Marseille (France), Musée d\'Archéologie Méditerranéenne - Centre de la Vieille Charité. The source also records the place Yémen, Ali Aqil, Azza.','https://collections.louvre.fr/en/ark:/53355/cl010167149','collections.louvre.fr'),(176,'0- _28_p031_19978641','Bardey, Pierre Acquisition details don Acquisition date date de comité/commission : 12/12/1912 date du conseil : 13/01/1913 Owned by Etat Held by Musée du Louvre, Département des Antiquités orientales Location of object Current location Marseille (France), Musée d\'Archéologie Méditerranéenne - Centre de la Vieille Charité Index Mode d\'acquisition don Name figurine Materials bronze Description/Features cheval - enfant - cavalier Places Yémen Ali Aqil, Azza ',544,NULL,'','Figurine, bronze, depicting a horse with a child rider. The object was acquired by donation and is held by the Musée du Louvre, Département des Antiquités orientales; current location: Marseille, Musée d\'Archéologie Méditerranéenne - Centre de la Vieille Charité.','Figurine, bronze, depicting a horse, a child, and a rider. The object was acquired by donation, with committee date 12/12/1912 and council date 13/01/1913. It is owned by the State and held by the Musée du Louvre, Département des Antiquités orientales. Current location: Marseille (France), Musée d\'Archéologie Méditerranéenne - Centre de la Vieille Charité. Place of origin or associated place: Yemen, Ali Aqil, Azza.','https://collections.louvre.fr/en/ark:/53355/cl010167149','collections.louvre.fr'),(177,'0- _4_p001_27d081fd','The Barakat Collection Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Sabean Silver Drachma , 300 BCE - 200 CE Silver/Gold FJ.5730 Enquire %3Cdiv%20class%3D%22title_and_year%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22title_and_year_title%22%3ESabean%20Silver%20Drachma%3C/span%3E%2C%20%3Cspan%20class%3D%22title_and_year_year%22%3E300%20BCE%20%20-%20%20200%20CE%3C/span%3E%3C/div%3E%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22medium%22%3ESilver/Gold%3C/div%3E Further images (View a larger image of thumbnail 1 ) (View a larger image of thumbnail 2 ) (View a larger image of thumbnail 3 ) The Sabeans were a semitic people who lived in the southwest corner of the Arabian peninsula in Saba (modern Yemen), a location that enabled them to play an important role... Read more The Sabeans were a semitic people who lived in the southwest corner of the Arabian peninsula in Saba (modern Yemen), a location that enabled them to play an important role in the economic life of the ancient Near East.',545,NULL,'','Coin, silver/gold, Sabean silver drachma, dated 300 BCE–200 CE.','Coin, silver/gold, Sabean silver drachma, dated 300 BCE–200 CE. The object is identified as a Sabean silver drachma and is described as made of silver/gold. The Sabeans were a Semitic people who lived in the southwest corner of the Arabian Peninsula in Saba (modern Yemen). Inventory number FJ.5730 is given in the source text.','https://barakatgallery.eu/artworks/57956-sabean-silver-drachma-300-bce-200-ce/','barakatgallery.com'),(178,'0- _4_p003_16facb8e','The Barakat Collection Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Sabaean Seated Statuette of a Woman , 600 BCE - 100 BCE Calcite-Alabaster height 20.3 cm height 8 in LA.550 Enquire %3Cdiv%20class%3D%22title_and_year%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22title_and_year_title%22%3ESabaean%20Seated%20Statuette%20of%20a%20Woman%3C/span%3E%2C%20%3Cspan%20class%3D%22title_and_year_year%22%3E600%20BCE%20%20-%20%20100%20BCE%3C/span%3E%3C/div%3E%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22medium%22%3ECalcite-Alabaster%3C/div%3E%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22dimensions%22%3Eheight%2020.3%20cm%3Cbr/%3E%0Aheight%208%20in%3C/div%3E The ancient kingdom of Saba ruled over the lands of southern Arabia, centered in modern day Yemen. In addition, a trade route that connected India to Egypt that passed through their capital of Marib was another major source of wealth.In the 1st Century A.D., the Ptolemaic Greeks discovered a sea route from India directly to the port of Alexandria, eliminating Saba from her lucrative trade and ushering in the decline of Sabean prosperity. Yet the pose of the figurine would indicate a probably southern provenance, as several early ones have been unearthed from Main, while the use of alabaster was widespread in Qataban. Although gold and silver deposits were present, the chief source of their vast wealth was derived from their veritable monopoly of two of the most coveted materials in ancient times: frankincense and myrrh, resinous gums obtained from certain trees that only grow in Southern Arabia and were literally worth their weight in gold. The female figure is seated wearing a long dress, her hands held before her, the ears and arms pierced,the lower arms projecting horizontally forward at right angles to the upper arms, in a gesture very common in such statuary. Saba is perhaps better known as Sheba, the Hebrew word for the kingdom, whose famous Queen was recounted as having visited Solomon in the pages of the Old Testament. Ruins of fortresses and walled towns are evident and remnants of their extensive irrigation system that turned the desert into a paradise still cover the land. Biblical accounts speak of the wealth of this ancient civilization of traders and merchants, and modern archaeological excavations confirm these reports.',550,NULL,'','Sabaean seated statuette of a woman, calcite-alabaster, dated 600 BCE–100 BCE, with a height of 20.3 cm. The female figure is seated wearing a long dress, with her hands held before her.','Sabaean seated statuette of a woman, calcite-alabaster, dated 600 BCE–100 BCE, height 20.3 cm. The female figure is seated and wears a long dress; her hands are held before her. The ears and arms are pierced, and the lower arms project horizontally forward at right angles to the upper arms, a gesture described as common in this type of statuary. The object is identified as Sabaean, with the text noting a probable southern provenance and mentioning that similar early examples have been unearthed from Main, while alabaster was widespread in Qataban.','https://barakatgallery.eu/artworks/60216-sabaean-seated-statuette-of-a-woman-600-bce-100-bce/','barakatgallery.com'),(179,'0- _4_p008_9905cdb4','Dimensions : Height: 14.25 in (36.2 cm) Width: 6.5 in (16.51 cm) Depth: 3 in (7.62 cm) Materials and Techniques : Limestone , Carved Place of Origin : Yemen Period : 15th Century and Earlier Date of Manufacture : 400 BC-100 BC Condition : Very Fine Condition. Category Early 20th Century American Folk Art Antiquities Materials Wood H 17 in W 14 in D 19 in American Country Taxidermy Bear Bust Wall Plaque Located in Queens, NY American Country style taxidermy bust of a brwon bear with it\'s mouth agape and mounted on a wooden plaque Category Early 20th Century American Rustic Antiquities H 0.2 in W 15.56 in D 15.56 in Antique Display Plate, Oriental, Cloisonne Plaque, Qing Dynasty, Georgian, 1750 Located in Hele, Devon, GB This is an antique display plate. Category 20th Century Greek Greek Revival Historical Memorabilia Materials Metal H 25 in W 45 in D 2 in American Mid-Century Gold World Map Plaque Located in Queens, NY American Mid-Century oval shaped metal wall plaque map of the world with gold continents in relief against a black grid. Category Antique 15th Century and Earlier Ecuadorean Pre-Columbian Antiquities Materials Gold H 10 in W 14 in Rustic Taxidermy Anter Plaque Located in Queens, NY Rustic taxidermy small antler wall plaque on round black backing (20th Cent.) Category 20th Century American Rustic Antiquities Materials Antler H 17 in W 19 in D 3 in Black Forest Carved Bird Plaque By Black Forest Located in Coeur d\'Alene, ID Swiss carved walnut plaque with game bird and two chicks with vine and leaf design. Category Antique Early 1900s Swiss Black Forest Wall-mounted Sculptures Materials Wood H 0.1 in W 12.5 in D 8.75 in Large Greek Style Repousse Oval Metal Plaque Located in Guaynabo, PR This is a large Greek style repousse oval metal plaque depicting a scene of a Spartan warrior trying to defend himself against two nudes warriors from another tribe. Category Vintage 1920s European Antiquities Materials Brass H 25 in W 45 in D 2 in American Mid-Century Gold World Map Plaque Located in Queens, NY American Mid-Century oval shaped metal wall plaque map of the world with gold continents in relief against a black grid. Category 20th Century Greek Greek Revival Historical Memorabilia Materials Metal H 9 in W 7 in D 1 in Hand Carved & Painted Wood Indian Chief Plaque Located in Los Angeles, CA Early 20thc Hand carved & painted Indian chief wood plaque. Learn More H 0.1 in W 12.5 in D 8.75 in Large Greek Style Repousse Oval Metal Plaque Located in Guaynabo, PR This is a large Greek style repousse oval metal plaque depicting a scene of a Spartan warrior trying to defend himself against two nudes warriors from another tribe.',559,NULL,'','Plaque, limestone, carved. Place of origin: Yemen. Date of manufacture: 400 BC-100 BC. Dimensions: height 36.2 cm, width 16.51 cm, depth 7.62 cm. Condition: very fine.','Plaque, limestone, carved. Place of origin: Yemen. Period: 15th century and earlier. Date of manufacture: 400 BC-100 BC. Dimensions: height 14.25 in (36.2 cm), width 6.5 in (16.51 cm), depth 3 in (7.62 cm). Condition: very fine.','https://www.1stdibs.com/furniture/folk-art/antiquities/sabean-funerary-stone-plaque/id-f_6213143/','1stdibs.com'),(180,'0- _4_p008_edea912b','The Barakat Collection Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Sabean Granite Head of a Woman , 600 BCE - 100 BCE Granite 24.1 x 10.8 cm 9 1/2 x 4 1/4 in LK.110 Enquire %3Cdiv%20class%3D%22title_and_year%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22title_and_year_title%22%3ESabean%20Granite%20Head%20of%20a%20Woman%3C/span%3E%2C%20%3Cspan%20class%3D%22title_and_year_year%22%3E600%20BCE%20%20-%20%20100%20BCE%3C/span%3E%3C/div%3E%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22medium%22%3EGranite%3C/div%3E%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22dimensions%22%3E24.1%20x%2010.8%20cm%3Cbr/%3E%0A9%201/2%20x%204%201/4%20in%3C/div%3E Further images (View a larger image of thumbnail 1 ) (View a larger image of thumbnail 2 ) (View a larger image of thumbnail 3 ) This striking head is an architectural fragment from a notable public or ceremonial building, and pertains to the ancient kingdom of Saba which ruled over the lands of southwestern Arabia,... The city of Marib was also in an ideal position to control the trade route between India to Egypt, although this lucrative venture was cut short in the 1st century AD following the foundation of a nautical route from India directly to the port of Alexandria. Read more This striking head is an architectural fragment from a notable public or ceremonial building, and pertains to the ancient kingdom of Saba which ruled over the lands of southwestern Arabia, centered in modern day Yemen. There are major works in bronze, precious metals and exotic minerals, but they are perhaps best known for works in stone such as alabaster and, in the present case, granite. The wealth of the kingdom was legendary, and was primarily attributable to Saba’s position at the crossroads of the ancient world, receiving consignments (particularly of incense) from all across the Middle East, Asia and the Mediterranean basin. Technically, the Sabeans are one of four major powers in this area, also including the Minaeans, the Qatabanians and the Hadramites, but the peoples as a whole became subsumed as a single entity by the middle of the first millennium BC. Their religion and mythology fuelled the themes of their sculptural works – primarily anthropomorphic and zoomorphic statuary – while their contact with other cultures and nations led to a highly derived and distinctive style. However, the breaks to the top, side and base of this piece suggest that it was architectural in origin, and may have served as a form of caryatid for a structure of social import to the society at the time.',560,NULL,'','Sabean head of a woman in granite, dated 600 BCE–100 BCE, measuring 24.1 x 10.8 cm. The object is an architectural fragment from the ancient kingdom of Saba.','Sabean head of a woman, granite, dated 600 BCE–100 BCE. The object measures 24.1 x 10.8 cm (9 1/2 x 4 1/4 in). It is described as an architectural fragment from a notable public or ceremonial building in the ancient kingdom of Saba, centered in modern-day Yemen. The piece is identified as a striking head and is noted for breaks to the top, side, and base, suggesting an architectural origin. The source states that it may have served as a caryatid for a structure of social importance. The Sabeans are described as being known for stone works, including alabaster and granite, and for a distinctive sculptural style shaped by religious and cultural contacts.','https://barakatgallery.eu/artworks/54706-sabean-granite-head-of-a-woman-600-bce-100-bce/','barakatgallery.com'),(181,'0- _4_p009_90e33534','The Barakat Collection Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Sabean Alabaster Relief of a Horned Bull , 200 BCE - 100 CE Alabaster 10.2 x 14 cm 4 1/8 x 5 1/2 in PF.0083 Enquire %3Cdiv%20class%3D%22title_and_year%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22title_and_year_title%22%3ESabean%20Alabaster%20Relief%20of%20a%20Horned%20Bull%3C/span%3E%2C%20%3Cspan%20class%3D%22title_and_year_year%22%3E200%20BCE%20%20-%20%20100%20CE%3C/span%3E%3C/div%3E%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22medium%22%3EAlabaster%3C/div%3E%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22dimensions%22%3E10.2%20x%2014%20cm%3Cbr/%3E%0A4%201/8%20x%205%201/2%20in%3C/div%3E Further images (View a larger image of thumbnail 1 ) (View a larger image of thumbnail 2 ) (View a larger image of thumbnail 3 ) (View a larger image of thumbnail 4 ) The ancient kingdom of Saba ruled over the lands of southern Arabia, centered in modern day Yemen. In the 1st Century A.D., the Ptolemaic Greeks discovered a sea route from India directly to the port of Alexandria, eliminating Saba from this lucrative trade and ushering in the decline of Sabean prosperity. Carved from one smooth block of alabaster, this beautiful high relief sculpture signifies an important period of art in the South Arabian region, using bold curves and delicate decoration. Although gold and silver deposits were present, the chief source of their vast wealth was derived from their veritable monopoly of two of the most coveted materials in ancient times: frankincense and myrrh, resinous gums obtained from certain trees that only grow in Southern Arabia and were literally worth their weight in gold. Perhaps their greatest accomplishment was the Great Dam of Marib, a monumental construction that brought water from the mountains both to the city and to the crop fields. The dam was in continual use (accounting for timely repairs) until the 6th Century A.D. Saba is perhaps better known as Sheba, the Hebrew word for the kingdom, whose famous Queen was recounted as having visited Solomon in the pages of the Old Testament. Ruins of fortresses and walled towns are evident and remnants of their extensive irrigation system that turned the desert into a paradise still cover the land.',561,NULL,'','Relief, alabaster. Sabean alabaster relief of a horned bull, dated 200 BCE–100 CE. Carved from one smooth block of alabaster; dimensions 10.2 x 14 cm (4 1/8 x 5 1/2 in).','Relief, alabaster. Sabean alabaster relief of a horned bull, dated 200 BCE–100 CE. The object is carved from one smooth block of alabaster and is described as a high relief sculpture with bold curves and delicate decoration. It measures 10.2 x 14 cm (4 1/8 x 5 1/2 in).','https://barakatgallery.eu/artworks/56867-sabean-alabaster-relief-of-a-horned-bull-200-bce-100-ce/','barakatgallery.com'),(182,'0-  30_p003_2e0f1399',': 19 cm Provenance : Ancienne collection Monsieur et Madame Antonin Besse Collection Monsieur et Madame Jean Sauvagnargues, fin des années 1950 Puis par descendance à l\'actuel propriétaire An alabaster South Arabian head of a bearded man, circa 1st century B.C. À vocation funéraire ou votive, ces représentations symboliques du défunt ou du fidèle pouvaient prendre la forme de stèles, statuettes ou masques comme ici. Jean Sauvagnargues (1915-2002), diplomate français, ancien ministre, ambassadeur de France en Ethiopie (1956-1960), en Tunisie (1962-1970) puis en Allemagne (1970-1974), reçut cette œuvre à la fin des années 1950 d\'Antonin Besse II. +33 1 42 99 20 51 bids@artcurial.com Actions E-Catalog Add to your Calendar Order the Catalog Terms & Conditions of Purchase 46 TÊTE MASCULINE EN ALBÂTRE Art sud-arabique, vers le 1er siècle av.J.C. Ce dernier hérita de la collection de son père, Sir Antonin Besse, éminent homme d\'affaires qui développa un véritable empire commercial et constitua une importante collection d\'œuvres d\'art. +33 1 42 99 20 51 bids@artcurial.com Actions E-Catalog Add to your Calendar Order the Catalog Terms & Conditions of Purchase Les yeux et sourcils étaient autrefois incrustés de divers matériaux visant à donner davantage vie à ces sculptures. Tête d\'homme aux yeux creux, autrefois incrustés, sourcils incisés, nez droit, coiffure courte et barbe en collier.',568,NULL,'','Head, alabaster. South Arabian male head with beard, circa 1st century B.C. The face has hollow eyes, formerly inlaid, incised eyebrows, a straight nose, short hair, and a collar beard.','Head, alabaster. South Arabian art, circa 1st century B.C. Male head with beard, probably intended for funerary or votive use, as symbolic representations of the deceased or the worshipper could take the form of stelae, statuettes, or masks. The sculpture has hollow eyes that were formerly inlaid with various materials, incised eyebrows, a straight nose, short hair, and a collar beard. The object is recorded as 19 cm high.','https://www.artcurial.com/en/sales/4042/lots/46-a','artcurial.com'),(183,'0-  30_p004_e96b4190','Tête de type \" Mariam \", au visage ovale, esquissant un léger sourire, le nez droit et les yeux creux en amande, le cou rectiligne, la chevelure tombant droit sur la nuque à l\'arrière des oreilles. +33 1 42 99 20 51 bids@artcurial.com Actions E-Catalog Add to your Calendar Order the Catalog Terms & Conditions of Purchase 27 TÊTE FÉMININE EN PIERRE, ARABIE DU SUD, FIN DU 1ER MILLÉNAIRE AV.J.C. (9 in.) A SOUTH ARABIAN STONE FEMALE HEAD, LATE 1ST MILLENIUM B.C. Estimate: €8,000 - 10,000 Sold : €19,306 Complete Description TÊTE FÉMININE EN PIERRE, ARABIE DU SUD, FIN DU 1ER MILLÉNAIRE AV.J.C. +33 1 42 99 20 51 bids@artcurial.com Actions E-Catalog Add to your Calendar Order the Catalog Terms & Conditions of Purchase Estimate: €8,000 - 10,000 Sold : €19,306 27 TÊTE FÉMININE EN PIERRE, ARABIE DU SUD, FIN DU 1ER MILLÉNAIRE AV.J.C. +33 1 42 99 20 20 ebailoni@artcurial.com Bids Office Kristina Vrzests Tel. 27 TÊTE FÉMININE EN PIERRE, ARABIE DU SUD, FIN DU 1ER MILLÉNAIRE AV.J.C.',569,NULL,'','Female head, stone, South Arabia, late 1st millennium B.C. Type \"Mariam\"; oval face with a slight smile, straight nose, hollow almond-shaped eyes, straight neck, and hair falling straight onto the nape behind the ears.','Female head, stone, South Arabia, late 1st millennium B.C. Type \"Mariam\". The head has an oval face with a slight smile, a straight nose, and hollow almond-shaped eyes. The neck is straight, and the hair falls straight onto the nape behind the ears. The description identifies the object as a female head in stone from South Arabia, dated to the late 1st millennium B.C.','https://www.artcurial.com/en/sales/2266/lots/27-a','artcurial.com'),(184,'0-  30_p005_10baea5a','Provenance: ex Bonhams, London, 5.7.2018, lot 164',570,NULL,'','','','https://drouot.com/en/l/31417835-head-of-a-man-sabaean-3rd-century-bc-1st-century-ad-h-28-5','drouot.com'),(185,'0-  30_p006_6686f187','Provenance Ex Numismatic Ancient Art Gallery AG, Zurich Ex Fondation Rassla, Suisse, dans les années 1970 A South Arabian Alabaster Head. LOT 71 TÊTE MASCULINE Albâtre, or et coquillage Dim. 15,5 x 11,4 x 7,5 cm Culture Sabbatéenne, IIIe-IIe siècle av. 15,5 x 11,4 x 7,5 cm Culture Sabbatéenne,... [ translate ] TÊTE MASCULINE Albâtre, or et coquillage Dim.',571,NULL,'','Head, alabaster with gold and shell, South Arabian, Sabaean culture, 3rd-2nd century BC. Dimensions: 15.5 x 11.4 x 7.5 cm.','Head, alabaster with gold and shell, from South Arabia. The object is identified as a male head and is attributed to the Sabaean culture, dated to the 3rd-2nd century BC. It measures 15.5 x 11.4 x 7.5 cm. Provenance information in the source mentions Ex Numismatic Ancient Art Gallery AG, Zurich, and Ex Fondation Rassla, Switzerland, in the 1970s.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/TETE-MASCULINE/71-tete_masculin