ze statuette of a kneeling king £1,500 - £2,000 A large Egyptian limestone shabti £2,000 - £3,000 An Egyptian green glazed faience shabti for Pa-Her-Mer, Overseer of the Treasury £1,200 - £1,800 An Egyptian pale green glazed faience shabti for the Overseer of the Treasury, Psamtek, \'Good name\', Iahmes, born to Bastet-ir-dis £2,000 - £3,000 An Egyptian gilded polychrome painted cartonnage mummy mask £3,000 - £5,000 An Egyptian polychrome painted cartonnage mummy mask Amended £2,000 - £3,000 Depicting a seated female figure, wearing a long tunic and an elaborate broad collar decorated with small round pendants and a large central circular medallion attached to a crescent-shaped pendant, with a long nose, almond-shaped eyes with pierced pupils and long hair arranged in plaits falling over the shoulders, both hands closed in a fist, 18½in (47cm) high Footnotes Provenance : American private collection, Los Angeles, formed in the 1970s. Find your local specialist Ask about this lot New Bond Street [email protected] Client Services (UK) Tel: +44 20 7447 7447 [email protected] Shipping (UK) Tel: +44 20 7468 8302 [email protected] A South Arabian limestone seated figure Circa 1st Century B.C. Buyers\' Premium and Charges For all Sales categories, buyer\'s premium excluding Cars, Motorbikes, Wine, Whisky and Coin & Medal sales, will be as follows: Buyer\'s Premium Rates 28% on the first £40,000 of the hammer price',574,NULL,'','Figure, limestone. South Arabian seated figure, depicted seated and carved in limestone, dated circa 1st century B.C. The figure is 18½ in (47 cm) high.','Figure, limestone. South Arabian seated figure carved in limestone, dated circa 1st century B.C. The object is described as a seated figure, with the preserved height given as 18½ in (47 cm). No further technical or contextual details are provided in the source text beyond the object type, material, cultural attribution, and date.','https://www.bonhams.com/auction/20668/lot/181/a-south-arabian-limestone-seated-figure/','bonhams.com'),(189,'0-  30_p010_82b6e20a','Standing male figure ca. late 1st millennium BCE Not on view This standing male figure is a funerary or votive object intended to be placed in a tomb or temple. Dressed in a long, plain garment reaching almost to the ankles, the figure stands in a fully frontal pose. The base, which is carved in one piece with the figure, bears the name of the individual and his clan—Sadiqim Ma\'ad. The eyes and eyebrows are carved to hold inlays, now missing, and the arms are bent at the elbows, extending out at right angles to the body. One hand is clenched in a fist, pierced vertically to hold some object, perhaps a scepter, now lost. The other hand is open. The undersurface of the base and the top and back of the figure\'s head are roughly carved. Such statues were often set in niches, and the surfaces not visible were consequently left unfinished on many examples. The placement of the ears high on the head, the aquiline nose, the small mouth, and the fully frontal pose are all characteristic of human images made in this region. Artwork Details Object Information Overview Provenance Exhibition History References Title: Standing male figure Date: ca. late 1st millennium BCE Geography: Southwestern Arabia Medium: Alabaster (calcite) Dimensions: H. 14 13/16 × W. 4 1/2 × D. 4 3/16 in. (37.6 × 11.5 × 10.7 cm) Credit Line: Purchase, Mr. and Mrs. Nathaniel Spear Jr. Gift, 1982 Object Number: 1982.317.3 Curatorial Department: Ancient West Asian Art More Artwork More Artwork Related From the same time and place A slider containing 5 items. Press the down key to skip to the last item. Votive or funerary stele ca. late 1st millennium BCE Relief panel ca. 883–859 BCE Human-headed winged bull (lamassu) ca. 883–859 BCE Relief panel ca. 883–859 BCE Relief panel ca. 883–859 BCE Related Content Timeline of Art History Entries and chronologies from The Met\'s art encyclopedia. Trade between Arabia and the Empires of Rome and Asia Arabian Peninsula, 1000 B.C.–1 A.D. Publications Books, guides, and catalogues published by The Met. Notable Acquisitions, 1982–1983 Free to Research Resources The Met provides unparalleled resources for research and welcomes an international community of students and scholars. The Met\'s Open Access API is where creators and researchers can connect to the The Met collection. Open Access data and public domain images are available for unrestricted commercial and noncommercial use without permission or fee. To request images under copyright and other restrictions, please use this Image Request form . Feedback We continue to research and examine historical and cultural context for objects in The Met collection. If you have comments or questions about this object record, please contact us using the form below. The Museum looks forward to receiving your comments. Send feedback Standing male figure ca. late 1st millennium BCE Not on view This standing male figure is a funerary or votive object intended to be placed in a tomb or temple. Dressed in a long, plain garment reaching almost to the ankles, the figure stands in a fully frontal pose. The base, which is carved in one piece with the figure, bears the name of the individual and his clan—Sadiqim Ma\'ad. The eyes and eyebrows are carved to hold inlays, now missing, and the arms are bent at the elbows, extending out at right angles to the body. One hand is clenched in a fist, pierced vertically to hold some object, perhaps a scepter, now lost. The other hand is open. The undersurface of the base and the top and back of the figure\'s head are roughly carved. Such statues were often set in niches, and the surfaces not visible were consequently left unfinished on many examples. The placement of the ears high on the head, the aquiline nose, the small mouth, and the fully frontal pose are all characteristic of human images made in this region.',575,NULL,'','Standing male figure, alabaster (calcite), ca. late 1st millennium BCE. Funerary or votive object carved in a fully frontal pose, with a long plain garment and a base inscribed with the name Sadiqim Ma\'ad.','Standing male figure, alabaster (calcite), ca. late 1st millennium BCE. This funerary or votive object was intended for placement in a tomb or temple. The figure stands frontally and wears a long, plain garment reaching almost to the ankles. It is carved in one piece with a base that bears the name of the individual and his clan, Sadiqim Ma\'ad. The eyes and eyebrows are carved to receive inlays, now missing. The arms are bent at the elbows and extend outward at right angles to the body; one hand is clenched in a fist and pierced vertically to hold an object, perhaps a scepter, now lost, while the other hand is open. The undersurface of the base and the top and back of the head are roughly carved, consistent with statues that were set in niches and left unfinished on non-visible surfaces. The ears are placed high on the head, and the aquiline nose, small mouth, and fully frontal pose are characteristic of human images made in southwestern Arabia.','https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/326695','metmuseum.org'),(190,'0-  30_p011_2fc817ec','Previous Lot Lot 152 Next Lot 1 / 4 Click To Zoom Condition Report Contact Information Auction Specialist Lot 152 Sale 6428 - Antiquities and Ancient Art: Including Property from the Estates of Andrew C. Provenance Condition Report Contact Information Auction Specialist Lot Description A South Arabian Alabaster Standing Worshipper Circa 4th-1st Century B.C. Estimate $30,000 - 50,000 Price Realized $19,200 Sold prices are inclusive of Buyer’s Premium Lot Description A South Arabian Alabaster Standing Worshipper Circa 4th-1st Century B.C. Love Nov 19, 2025 10:00AM CT Live / Chicago Own a similar item?',576,19200,'USD','Standing worshipper, alabaster, South Arabian, circa 4th-1st century B.C.','Standing worshipper, alabaster, South Arabian, circa 4th-1st century B.C. The object is identified as a South Arabian alabaster standing worshipper and is dated to the circa 4th-1st century B.C. No further technical, dimensional, or contextual details are provided in the source text.','https://freemansauction.com/auctions/6428-antiquities-and-ancient-art/lot/152?fromSearch=true','freemansauction.com'),(191,'0-  30_p012_4aa6b43c','Bibliographie : F.Demange, L\'Homme de Bronze, Actualité du Département des Antiquités Orientales n°10, Musée du Louvre, Paris, mai-octobre 2007 Ce type de statue votive, réalisée à l\'image du fidèle, trouve son parallèle dans trois autres sculptures en bronze du Musée de Sanaa, dont l\'une, dédiée au dieu tutélaire du royaume de Saba, Almaqah, a été restaurée par le Musée du Louvre. +33 1 42 99 20 51 bids@artcurial.com Actions E-Catalog Add to your Calendar Order the Catalog Terms & Conditions of Purchase 72 STATUE MASCULINE EN BRONZE, ARABIE DU SUD, 6EME SIÈCLE AV.J.C. Estimate: €40,000 - 60,000 Sold : €91,200 Complete Description STATUE MASCULINE EN BRONZE, ARABIE DU SUD, 6EME SIÈCLE AV.J.C. La datation qui nous en est donnée est étayée par le traitement stylistique du vêtement, dont le drapé évoque celui des frises achéménides de Persépolis et dont la coiffure rappelle celle en boucles volutiformes des Assyriens, Perses et Grecs du 6e siècle avant Jésus-Christ. Estimate: €40,000 - 60,000 Sold : €91,200 72 STATUE MASCULINE EN BRONZE, ARABIE DU SUD, 6EME SIÈCLE AV.J.C. Sculpture ex-voto représentant un homme debout, le bras droit plié, le gauche près du corps, poings fermés percés, vêtu d\'un pagne plissé moulant les hanches jusqu\'aux genoux, croisé et ouvert sur le devant et maintenu par une ceinture. (9 ½ in.) A SOUTH ARABIAN BRONZE VOTIVE SCULPTURE OF A MAN, 6TH CENTURY B.C. 72 STATUE MASCULINE EN BRONZE, ARABIE DU SUD, 6EME SIÈCLE AV.J.C.',577,NULL,'','Bronze votive statue of a man, South Arabian, 6th century B.C. The standing figure has the right arm bent, the left arm close to the body, and clenched fists pierced through. It wears a pleated loincloth fitted over the hips to the knees, crossed and open at the front, and held by a belt.','Bronze votive statue of a man, South Arabian, 6th century B.C. This ex-voto sculpture represents a standing male figure with the right arm bent and the left arm held close to the body; the fists are clenched and pierced. The figure is dressed in a pleated loincloth moulded to the hips and extending to the knees, crossed and open at the front, and secured by a belt. The dating given in the source is supported by the stylistic treatment of the garment, whose drapery recalls the Achaemenid friezes of Persepolis, and by the hairstyle, described as volute-like curls comparable to those of Assyrians, Persians, and Greeks of the 6th century B.C.','https://www.artcurial.com/en/sales/2266/lots/72-a','artcurial.com'),(192,'0-  30_p013_d3799f39','Statue en bronze, représentant un personnage debout, bras pliés en avant, poings fermés, debout, vêtu d\'une jupe droite s\'arrêtant au niveau des mollets, d\'une chemise moulante à manches longues et encolure en pointe. (12 in.) A SOUTH ARABIAN BRONZE INSCRIBED FEMALE FIGURE, 1ST CENTURY B.C.-A.D. +33 1 42 99 20 51 bids@artcurial.com Actions E-Catalog Add to your Calendar Order the Catalog Terms & Conditions of Purchase 64 STATUE FÉMININE, PÉNINSULE ARABIQUE, 1ER SIÈCLE AV.-AP.J.C. Estimate: €60,000 - 70,000 Sold : €61,200 Complete Description STATUE FÉMININE, PÉNINSULE ARABIQUE, 1ER SIÈCLE AV.-AP.J.C. La tête, au masque triangulaire, comporte de grands yeux en amande et des sourcils légèrement arqués prolongeant l\'arête d\'un nez droit ',578,NULL,'','Statue, bronze, of a standing female figure with arms bent forward and clenched fists, wearing a straight skirt ending at mid-calf and a close-fitting long-sleeved shirt with a pointed neckline. South Arabian, 1st century B.C.-A.D.','Statue, bronze, representing a standing female figure with the arms bent forward and the fists closed. The figure wears a straight skirt ending at mid-calf and a close-fitting long-sleeved shirt with a pointed neckline. The head has a triangular mask-like appearance, with large almond-shaped eyes, slightly arched eyebrows, and a straight nose bridge. South Arabian, 1st century B.C.-A.D.','https://www.artcurial.com/en/sales/2192/lots/64-a','artcurial.com'),(193,'0-  30_p014_9bc22dd3','Votive plaque inscribed with Sabaean dedication ca. late 1st millennium BCE Not on view This votive plaque with a raised border around its edges has a Sabaean dedicatory inscription. While the worship of aniconic images was widespread among South Arabian cultures, the precise significance of the inscription as a cult object is uncertain. The practice of dedicating the inscription itself, as opposed to placing the inscription on an object intended for dedication, is a departure from the contemporary customs of greater Mesopotamia and Iran. Artwork Details Object Information Overview Provenance References Title: Votive plaque inscribed with Sabaean dedication Date: ca. late 1st millennium BCE Geography: Southwestern Arabia Medium: Copper alloy Dimensions: 10 7/8 × 6 × 1/2 in. (27.6 × 15.2 × 1.3 cm) Credit Line: Pfeiffer Fund, 1993 Object Number: 1993.169 Curatorial Department: Ancient West Asian Art More Artwork More Artwork Related From the same time and place A slider containing 5 items. Press the down key to skip to the last item. Incense burner ca. mid-1st millennium BCE Standing male figure ca. late 1st millennium BCE Votive or funerary stele ca. late 1st millennium BCE Gold Neck Ring 6th–4th century BCE Furniture element carved in the round with the head of a roaring lion ca. 9th–8th century BCE Related Content Timeline of Art History Entries and chronologies from The Met\'s art encyclopedia. Trade between Arabia and the Empires of Rome and Asia Arabian Peninsula, 1000 B.C.–1 A.D. Research Resources The Met provides unparalleled resources for research and welcomes an international community of students and scholars. The Met\'s Open Access API is where creators and researchers can connect to the The Met collection. Open Access data and public domain images are available for unrestricted commercial and noncommercial use without permission or fee. To request images under copyright and other restrictions, please use this Image Request form . Feedback We continue to research and examine historical and cultural context for objects in The Met collection. If you have comments or questions about this object record, please contact us using the form below. The Museum looks forward to receiving your comments. Send feedback Votive plaque inscribed with Sabaean dedication ca. late 1st millennium BCE Not on view This votive plaque with a raised border around its edges has a Sabaean dedicatory inscription. While the worship of aniconic images was widespread among South Arabian cultures, the precise significance of the inscription as a cult object is uncertain. The practice of dedicating the inscription itself, as opposed to placing the inscription on an object intended for dedication, is a departure from the contemporary customs of greater Mesopotamia and Iran.',579,NULL,'','Votive plaque, copper alloy, with a raised border and a Sabaean dedicatory inscription, from southwestern Arabia, ca. late 1st millennium BCE.','Votive plaque, copper alloy, with a raised border around the edges and a Sabaean dedicatory inscription, from southwestern Arabia, ca. late 1st millennium BCE. The plaque measures 10 7/8 × 6 × 1/2 in. (27.6 × 15.2 × 1.3 cm). The inscription is described as a dedicatory text, and the object is identified as a votive plaque; the precise significance of the inscription as a cult object is uncertain. The record notes that the practice of dedicating the inscription itself, rather than placing the inscription on an object intended for dedication, differs from contemporary customs in greater Mesopotamia and Iran.','https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/327483','metmuseum.org'),(194,'0-  30_p016_52fdfd6f','Inscription [Transliteration] l-B\'n [Translation] Belonging to Ba\'an Provenance Provenance (from the French provenir , \'to come from/forth\') is the chronology of the ownership, custody, or location of a historical object. Skip to main content Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Seal with an Inscription Thumbnail Seal with an Inscription South Arabian (Sculptor) 6th-5th century BCE chalcedony (South Arabia) Pierced lengthwise, this seal could have been mounted on a finger ring or strung on a necklace as an amulet. Notify the curator Creative Commons License Creative Commons Zero Image Zoom arrow_forward_ios arrow_forward_ios Seal with an Inscription Thumbnail Seal with an Inscription South Arabian (Sculptor) 6th-5th century BCE chalcedony (South Arabia) Pierced lengthwise, this seal could have been mounted on a finger ring or strung on a necklace as an amulet. (1.8 x 1.2 x 0.5 cm) Credit Line Gift of Giraud and Carolyn Foster, 2007 Location in Museum Not on view Accession Number In libraries, galleries, museums, and archives, an accession number is a unique identifier assigned to each object in the collection. Notify the curator Seal with an Inscription South Arabian (Sculptor) 6th-5th century BCE chalcedony (South Arabia) Pierced lengthwise, this seal could have been mounted on a finger ring or strung on a necklace as an amulet. Only the middle section of the seal is readable',581,NULL,'','Seal with inscription, chalcedony, South Arabian, 6th-5th century BCE. Pierced lengthwise, it may have been mounted on a finger ring or strung on a necklace as an amulet. Only the middle section of the seal is readable.','Seal with inscription, chalcedony, South Arabian, 6th-5th century BCE. The seal is pierced lengthwise and could have been mounted on a finger ring or strung on a necklace as an amulet. The inscription is transliterated as l-B\'n and translated as \"Belonging to Ba\'an.\" Only the middle section of the seal is readable. Dimensions: 1.8 x 1.2 x 0.5 cm.','https://art.thewalters.org/object/42.1512/','metmuseum.org'),(195,'0-  30_p017_6c61750c','Lot 122 122 A SOUTH ARABIAN LIMESTONE PILLAR STELE CIRCA 2ND CENTURY B.C.-2ND CENTURY A.D. Details A SOUTH ARABIAN LIMESTONE PILLAR STELE Circa 2nd Century B.C.-2nd Century A.D. Rectangular in form, sculpted at the upper end with the head of a bearded man in high relief, his beard and hair both rendered by echeloned curls, with a sharp brow, long triangular nose and thin, closed lips, the eyes raised with the pupils deeply recessed, an inscription below identifying the deceased 12¾ in. (32.4 cm.) high Provenance Anonymous sale',582,NULL,'','Stele, limestone, South Arabian, rectangular in form and sculpted at the upper end with the head of a bearded man in high relief, circa 2nd century B.C.-2nd century A.D.','Stele, limestone, South Arabian, rectangular in form and sculpted at the upper end with the head of a bearded man in high relief. The beard and hair are rendered by echeloned curls, and the face has a sharp brow, long triangular nose, thin closed lips, raised eyes with deeply recessed pupils. An inscription below identifies the deceased. Dated circa 2nd century B.C.-2nd century A.D. Height 12¾ in. (32.4 cm.).','https://www.christies.com/en/lot/lot-4205318','christies.com'),(196,'0-  30_p018_880a3521','Incense burner ca. mid-1st millennium BCE Not on view This bronze incense burner from southwestern Arabia consists of a cylindrical cup set on a conical base. A rectangular architectural form suggesting a facade extends upward from the cup’s front. Its face is decorated with two serpents flanking a round disk set within a crescent, all in low relief. Cast separately, an ibex standing on a plinth projects from the front of the incense burner and may serve as a handle. From the middle of the first millennium B.C. until the sixth century A.D., the kingdoms of southwestern Arabia gained considerable wealth and power through their control of the trade in incense between Arabia and the lands of the Mediterranean seacoast. Frankincense and myrrh, gum resins that are native to southern Arabia, were widely valued in the ancient world for the preparation of incense, perfumes, cosmetics, and medicines, as well as for use in religious and funerary ceremonies. The importance of incense in the religion of southwestern Arabia is reflected in this object',583,NULL,'','Incense burner, bronze, from southwestern Arabia, ca. mid-1st millennium BCE. It has a cylindrical cup on a conical base, with a rectangular architectural facade rising from the front, decorated in low relief with two serpents flanking a round disk within a crescent. A separately cast ibex on a plinth projects from the front and may have served as a handle.','Incense burner, bronze, from southwestern Arabia, dated to ca. mid-1st millennium BCE. The vessel consists of a cylindrical cup set on a conical base, with a rectangular architectural form rising from the front of the cup and suggesting a facade. The facade is decorated in low relief with two serpents flanking a round disk set within a crescent. A separately cast ibex standing on a plinth projects from the front of the burner and may have functioned as a handle. The object is associated with the importance of incense in the religion of southwestern Arabia.','https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/324075','metmuseum.org'),(197,'0-  30_p020_5b4e7eb9','Standing bull ca. mid- to late 1st millennium BCE Not on view This bronze bull stands on a double-based plinth. Its head is strongly sculpted with upright ears behind horns that curve up and slightly inward. Heavy brows arch over the eyes, which are inlaid with shell. The tail hangs straight down to the hooves and parallels those of southwestern Arabian statues of standing bulls sculpted in alabaster, suggesting that this piece dates to the late first millennium B.C. like the alabaster bulls. By the middle of the first millennium B.C., kingdoms had emerged in southwestern Arabia whose power was based on control of the trade in frankincense and myrrh, which are native to the region. The kingdoms\' immense wealth is reflected in the use of bronze to cast large sculptures, as well as smaller objects, which were produced throughout most of the first millennium B.C. Bulls are commonly represented and can be found on funerary stelae, seals, and sculpture. Artwork Details Object Information Overview Provenance References Title: Standing bull Date: ca. mid- to late 1st millennium BCE Geography: Southwestern Arabia Medium: Copper alloy, shell Dimensions: H. 9 1/2 × W. 3 1/2 × D. 9 3/8 in. (24.2 × 8.9 × 23.8 cm) Base: L. 7 1/16 in. × W. 3 1/2 in. (18 × 8.9 cm) Credit Line: Purchase, Michael Ward and Friends of Inanna Gifts, 2002 Object Number: 2002.34 Curatorial Department: Ancient West Asian Art More Artwork More Artwork Related In the same medium From the same time and place A slider containing 5 items. Press the down key to skip to the last item. Incense burner ca. mid-1st millennium BCE Standing male figure ca. late 1st millennium BCE Votive or funerary stele ca. late 1st millennium BCE Furniture element carved in the round with the head of a roaring lion ca. 9th–8th century BCE Figure of a lion late 1st millennium BCE Related Content Publications Books, guides, and catalogues published by The Met. \"Recent Acquisitions, A Selection: 2001–2002\" Free to Research Resources The Met provides unparalleled resources for research and welcomes an international community of students and scholars. The Met\'s Open Access API is where creators and researchers can connect to the The Met collection. Open Access data and public domain images are available for unrestricted commercial and noncommercial use without permission or fee. To request images under copyright and other restrictions, please use this Image Request form . Feedback We continue to research and examine historical and cultural context for objects in The Met collection. If you have comments or questions about this object record, please contact us using the form below. The Museum looks forward to receiving your comments. Send feedback Standing bull ca. mid- to late 1st millennium BCE Not on view This bronze bull stands on a double-based plinth. Its head is strongly sculpted with upright ears behind horns that curve up and slightly inward. Heavy brows arch over the eyes, which are inlaid with shell. The tail hangs straight down to the hooves and parallels those of southwestern Arabian statues of standing bulls sculpted in alabaster, suggesting that this piece dates to the late first millennium B.C. like the alabaster bulls. By the middle of the first millennium B.C., kingdoms had emerged in southwestern Arabia whose power was based on control of the trade in frankincense and myrrh, which are native to the region. The kingdoms\' immense wealth is reflected in the use of bronze to cast large sculptures, as well as smaller objects, which were produced throughout most of the first millennium B.C. Bulls are commonly represented and can be found on funerary stelae, seals, and sculpture.',585,NULL,'','Standing bull, copper alloy and shell, ca. mid- to late 1st millennium BCE. The bronze bull stands on a double-based plinth and has a strongly sculpted head with upright ears, horns curving up and slightly inward, heavy brows, and shell-inlaid eyes.','Standing bull, copper alloy and shell. This bronze bull stands on a double-based plinth and dates to ca. mid- to late 1st millennium BCE. The head is strongly sculpted, with upright ears set behind horns that curve upward and slightly inward. Heavy brows arch over the eyes, which are inlaid with shell. The tail hangs straight down to the hooves. The form is compared in the source text to standing bulls from southwestern Arabia sculpted in alabaster.','https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/328941','metmuseum.org'),(198,'0-  30_p021_65971c7e','Figure of ibex ca. 5th century BCE Not on view This bronze ibex stands on a base. Its distinctive long horns turn back to touch the upright ears. The ibex was the most widely represented animal in southwestern Arabian art. Ritual ibex hunts were an important feature of the cult practices of the southwestern Arabian kingdoms. Successfully capturing and killing these elusive creatures was believed to secure favors from the gods. This sculpture may have served as a handle for an incense burner similar to one in the Museum’s collection (MMA 49.71.2). From the middle of the first millennium B.C. until the sixth century A.D., the kingdoms of southwestern Arabia gained considerable wealth and power through their control of the trade in incense between Arabia and the lands of the Mediterranean seacoast. Frankincense and myrrh, gum resins that are native to southern Arabia, were widely valued in the ancient world for the preparation of incense, perfumes, cosmetics, and medicines, as well as for use in religious and funerary ceremonies. Artwork Details Object Information Overview Provenance Exhibition History References Title: Figure of ibex Date: ca. 5th century BCE Geography: Southwestern Arabia Medium: Bronze Dimensions: H. 5 1/16 × W. 1 1/2 × D. 2 15/16 in. (12.8 × 3.8 × 7.4 cm) Base: W. 1 5/16 in. × D. 2 5/16 in. (3.3 × 5.8 cm) Credit Line: Gift of Alastair Bradley Martin, 1953 Object Number: 53.47.2 Curatorial Department: Ancient West Asian Art More Artwork More Artwork Related In the same medium From the same time and place A slider containing 5 items. Press the down key to skip to the last item. Incense burner ca. mid-1st millennium BCE Standing male figure ca. late 1st millennium BCE Votive or funerary stele ca. late 1st millennium BCE Furniture element carved in the round with the head of a roaring lion ca. 9th–8th century BCE Top for standard ca. 8th century BCE Related Content Publications Books, guides, and catalogues published by The Met. Bronze and Iron: Ancient Near Eastern Artifacts in The Metropolitan Museum of Art Free to Research Resources The Met provides unparalleled resources for research and welcomes an international community of students and scholars. The Met\'s Open Access API is where creators and researchers can connect to the The Met collection. Open Access data and public domain images are available for unrestricted commercial and noncommercial use without permission or fee. To request images under copyright and other restrictions, please use this Image Request form . Feedback We continue to research and examine historical and cultural context for objects in The Met collection. If you have comments or questions about this object record, please contact us using the form below. The Museum looks forward to receiving your comments. Send feedback Figure of ibex ca. 5th century BCE Not on view This bronze ibex stands on a base. Its distinctive long horns turn back to touch the upright ears. The ibex was the most widely represented animal in southwestern Arabian art. Ritual ibex hunts were an important feature of the cult practices of the southwestern Arabian kingdoms. Successfully capturing and killing these elusive creatures was believed to secure favors from the gods. This sculpture may have served as a handle for an incense burner similar to one in the Museum’s collection (MMA 49.71.2). From the middle of the first millennium B.C. until the sixth century A.D., the kingdoms of southwestern Arabia gained considerable wealth and power through their control of the trade in incense between Arabia and the lands of the Mediterranean seacoast. Frankincense and myrrh, gum resins that are native to southern Arabia, were widely valued in the ancient world for the preparation of incense, perfumes, cosmetics, and medicines, as well as for use in religious and funerary ceremonies.',586,NULL,'','Figure of ibex, bronze, ca. 5th century BCE. A bronze ibex stands on a base, with long horns curving back to touch the upright ears.','Figure of ibex, bronze, ca. 5th century BCE. This small bronze sculpture depicts an ibex standing on a base, with distinctive long horns turning back to touch the upright ears. It is from Southwestern Arabia and measures H. 5 1/16 × W. 1 1/2 × D. 2 15/16 in. (12.8 × 3.8 × 7.4 cm); base: W. 1 5/16 in. × D. 2 5/16 in. (3.3 × 5.8 cm). The object may have served as a handle for an incense burner.','https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/324255','metmuseum.org'),(199,'0-  30_p026_bffdbce6','Previous Lot Lot 153 Next Lot 1 / 4 Click To Zoom Condition Report Contact Information Auction Specialist Lot 153 Sale 6428 - Antiquities and Ancient Art: Including Property from the Estates of Andrew C. Provenance Condition Report Contact Information Auction Specialist Lot Description A South Arabian Fragmentary Albaster Ibex Base Circa 4th-3rd Century B.C. Estimate $1,200 - 1,800 Price Realized $1,920 Sold prices are inclusive of Buyer’s Premium Lot Description A South Arabian Fragmentary Albaster Ibex Base Circa 4th-3rd Century B.C. Love Nov 19, 2025 10:00AM CT Live / Chicago Own a similar item?',591,1920,'USD','Fragmentary alabaster ibex base, South Arabian, circa 4th-3rd century B.C.','Fragmentary alabaster ibex base, South Arabian, circa 4th-3rd century B.C. The object is described as a base in fragmentary condition and is identified as South Arabian. No further technical details, dimensions, or decorative features are provided in the source text.','https://freemansauction.com/auctions/6428-antiquities-and-ancient-art/lot/153?fromSearch=true','freemansauction.com'),(200,'0-  30_p027_144a55e3','Freeman’s 1 / 4 Search',592,NULL,'','','','https://freemansauction.com/auctions/6428-antiquities-and-ancient-art/lot/154/preview?index=0','freemansauction.com'),(201,'0- _22_p004_4c5b844c','The Barakat Collection Open a larger version of the following image in a popup: Sabean Alabaster Bust of a Woman , 200 BCE - 100 CE Alabaster 12.1 x 19.1 cm 4 3/4 x 7 1/2 in PF.0084 (LSO) Enquire %3Cdiv%20class%3D%22title_and_year%22%3E%3Cspan%20class%3D%22title_and_year_title%22%3ESabean%20Alabaster%20Bust%20of%20a%20Woman%3C/span%3E%2C%20%3Cspan%20class%3D%22title_and_year_year%22%3E200%20BCE%20%20-%20%20100%20CE%3C/span%3E%3C/div%3E%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22medium%22%3EAlabaster%3C/div%3E%3Cdiv%20class%3D%22dimensions%22%3E12.1%20x%2019.1%20cm%3Cbr/%3E%0A4%203/4%20x%207%201/2%20in%3C/div%3E This striking head is a grave marker or perhaps a commemorative piece from the ancient kingdom of Saba which ruled over the lands of southwestern Arabia, centered in modern day... The city of Marib was also in an ideal position to control the trade route between India to Egypt, although this lucrative venture was cut short in the 1st century AD following the foundation of a nautical route from India directly to the port of Alexandria. Detailing is limited, with incised eyebrows and a single line at the apex of the forehead that seems designed to suggest a headband or similar. Read more This striking head is a grave marker or perhaps a commemorative piece from the ancient kingdom of Saba which ruled over the lands of southwestern Arabia, centered in modern day Yemen. The wealth of the kingdom is legendary, and is primarily attributable to Saba’s position at the crossroads of the ancient world, receiving consignments (particularly of incense) from all across the Middle East, Asia and the Mediterranean basin. Technically, the Sabeans were one of four major powers in this area, also including the Minaeans, the Qatabanians and the Hadramites, but the peoples as a whole became subsumed as a single entity by the middle of the first millennium BC. This piece depicts a feminine head and neck, and appears to have once served as a grave marker, or perhaps as part of a larger alabaster structure. Their religion and mythology fuelled the themes of their sculptural works – primarily anthropomorphic and zoomorphic statuary – while their contact with other cultures and nations led to a highly derived and distinctive style.',593,NULL,'','Bust, alabaster. Sabean alabaster bust of a woman, dated 200 BCE–100 CE, with dimensions of 12.1 x 19.1 cm. The piece depicts a feminine head and neck with limited detailing, including incised eyebrows and a single line at the apex of the forehead.','Bust, alabaster. Sabean alabaster bust of a woman, dated 200 BCE–100 CE, measuring 12.1 x 19.1 cm (4 3/4 x 7 1/2 in). The object depicts a feminine head and neck and is described as a striking head that may have served as a grave marker or perhaps as a commemorative piece from the ancient kingdom of Saba in southwestern Arabia, centered in modern-day Yemen. Detailing is limited, with incised eyebrows and a single line at the apex of the forehead that appears to suggest a headband or similar feature. The text also notes that it may once have formed part of a larger alabaster structure.','https://barakatgallery.eu/artworks/54789-sabean-alabaster-bust-of-a-woman-200-bce-100-ce/','barakatgallery.com'),(202,'0- _22_p008_e6f7e902','picture Auction 51 Part I - Books Chassidism Manuscripts Rabbinical Letters July 11, 2016 PDF Results Prices Realized Browse Sale << Previous Lot Lot 212 Next Lot >> Three Manuscripts - Passover Haggadah - Yemen Opening: $300 Sold for: $375 Including buyer\'s premium Passover Haggadah - three Yemenite manuscripts: · Manuscript, Passover Haggadah. Ask about this lot Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents << Previous Lot Next Lot >> View Details After the Haggadah: \"A nice bakashah, praise to the King…\", by Rabbi Yitzchak ben Yefet. With instructions and commentaries on the margins, some with nikud elyon. 3 handwritten Haggadot, size and condition vary (overall fair condition). · Manuscript, Passover Haggadah, with Judeo-Arabic translation. Lacking at the beginning and at the end.',596,375,'USD','Three manuscripts, Passover Haggadah, Yemenite, handwritten on paper, including one with instructions and commentaries on the margins, some with nikud elyon, and one with Judeo-Arabic translation. Size and condition vary; overall fair condition.','Three manuscripts, Passover Haggadah, Yemenite, handwritten on paper. The group includes a manuscript described as \"A nice bakashah, praise to the King…\", by Rabbi Yitzchak ben Yefet, with instructions and commentaries on the margins, some with nikud elyon; a second handwritten Haggadah; and a third manuscript, Passover Haggadah, with Judeo-Arabic translation, lacking at the beginning and at the end. Size and condition vary, with overall fair condition.','https://www.kedem-auctions.com/en/content/three-manuscripts-passover-haggadah-yemen','kedem-auctions.com'),(203,'0- _22_p009_ab2ed43b','picture picture 2 PHOTOS Auction 51 Part I - Books Chassidism Manuscripts Rabbinical Letters July 11, 2016 PDF Results Prices Realized Browse Sale << Previous Lot Lot 214 Next Lot >> Manuscript, Menorat HaMaor - Sana\'a, Yemen, 1848 Opening: $500 Sold for: $1,875 Including buyer\'s premium Manuscript, Menorat HaMaor, by Rabbi Yitzchak Abuhav. Ask about this lot Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents << Previous Lot Next Lot >> View Details At the beginning of each \"Ner\" (name of chapter in the book Menorat HaMaor) is a red and black ornamentation [with the exception of the sixth and seventh Ner]. Menorat HaMaor was embraced by Yemenite Jews and their communities adopted the custom of reading this composition in their synagogues every Shabbat afternoon. This is a complete manuscript of the composition (with the exception of a number of index leaves missing at the end), written before this well-known printing. Title page illustrated with a frame (in two colors): \"The book Menorat HaMaor was written by Rabbi Yitzchak Abuhav the Sephardi…written here in Sana\'a…1848\". In 1857, Rabbi Moshe Chanoch HaLevi, a Jew from Aden who reached Italy, printed an edition of Menorat HaMaor in Livorno for his Yemenite brethren. For this purpose, the book was divided into chapters for Shabbat and festival days throughout the year.',597,NULL,'','Manuscript on paper, Menorat HaMaor by Rabbi Yitzchak Abuhav, written in Sana\'a, Yemen, 1848. Complete manuscript with the exception of several index leaves missing at the end, decorated with red and black ornamentation at the beginning of each chapter, except the sixth and seventh chapters.','Manuscript on paper, Menorat HaMaor by Rabbi Yitzchak Abuhav, written in Sana\'a, Yemen, 1848. The manuscript is described as complete, apart from a number of index leaves missing at the end. At the beginning of each Ner, or chapter, there is red and black ornamentation, with the exception of the sixth and seventh Ners. The title page is illustrated with a two-colour frame and states that the book Menorat HaMaor was written by Rabbi Yitzchak Abuhav the Sephardi and written here in Sana\'a in 1848. The text notes that Menorat HaMaor was widely embraced by Yemenite Jews and read in synagogues on Shabbat afternoon.','https://www.kedem-auctions.com/en/content/manuscript-menorat-hamaor-sanaa-yemen-1848','kedem-auctions.com'),(204,'0- _22_p010_7fb500f3','picture Auction 51 Part I - Books Chassidism Manuscripts Rabbinical Letters July 11, 2016 PDF Results Prices Realized Browse Sale << Previous Lot Lot 215 Next Lot >> Manuscript, Mipi Chachamim - Yemen, 1895 Opening: $500 Sold for: $875 Including buyer\'s premium Manuscript, Mipi Chachamim, halachic, aggadic and kabbalistic explanations for various laws and customs. Ask about this lot Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents << Previous Lot Next Lot >> View Details This manuscript has many variations from the printed version and corresponds to another manuscript written nine months earlier by the same scribe Rabbi Oded son of Yafet in the month of Iyar 1894, \"by the desire of my master, Zecharya\". · Long letter to \"My master and crown of my head\" Rabbi Salam son of Menachem, by \"Yuda Nissim, and Chassan Yuda, and Machbuv Avni\". Interesting letter related to Aliya to Eretz Israel and about their travails \"that G-d confronted us with a foe like Haman and even worse than Haman, his name and memory should be erased…\". Colophon of the scribe Rabbi Oded son of Yafet [Ra\'avad of Aden, Ibb district, Southern Yemen] who wrote it \"by the desire of Chassan Utz and his sons\". [133] leaves, 25 cm + 9 leaves of varied size. On the endpapers and on additional leaves at the beginning and end are ownership inscriptions and various lists: · Prayers.',598,NULL,'','Manuscript, paper, Mipi Chachamim, containing halachic, aggadic, and kabbalistic explanations of various laws and customs, Yemen, 1895.','Manuscript, paper, Mipi Chachamim, with halachic, aggadic, and kabbalistic explanations for various laws and customs. The manuscript is described as having many variations from the printed version and as corresponding to another manuscript written nine months earlier by the same scribe, Rabbi Oded son of Yafet, in Iyar 1894, by the desire of his master, Zecharya. It includes a long letter addressed to Rabbi Salam son of Menachem by Yuda Nissim, Chassan Yuda, and Machbuv Avni, concerning aliyah to Eretz Israel and their travails, and contains a colophon by the scribe Rabbi Oded son of Yafet, identified as Ra\'avad of Aden, Ibb district, Southern Yemen, stating that he wrote it by the desire of Chassan Utz and his sons. The manuscript comprises 133 leaves, with an additional 9 leaves of varied size, measures 25 cm, and has ownership inscriptions and various lists, including prayers, on the endpapers and on additional leaves at the beginning and end.','https://www.kedem-auctions.com/en/content/manuscript-mipi-chachamim-yemen-1895','kedem-auctions.com'),(205,'0- _22_p011_683adcce','picture Auction 51 Part I - Books Chassidism Manuscripts Rabbinical Letters July 11, 2016 PDF Results Prices Realized Browse Sale << Previous Lot Lot 217 Next Lot >> Three Manuscripts - Yemen Opening: $500 Sold for: $1,750 Including buyer\'s premium Compilation of manuscripts, Scriptures and Targum. Ask about this lot Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents << Previous Lot Next Lot >> View Details · Three Megillot (Shir HaShirim, Ruth and Kohelet), with Targum, Rashi commentary and compiled novellae (by Mahari Tzalach, etc.). 3 manuscripts, two are approximately 23-24 cm. Leaves of Parshat Bereshit with Rashi commentary are bound at the beginning and end of manuscript. · Bereshit with Targum and Rashi commentary, Haftarot. With Gevil cover, from the geniza of a Sefer Torah. · Targum of Shir HaShirim, Ruth and Kohelet.',599,1750,'USD','Three manuscripts, on paper and gevil, comprising Megillot Shir HaShirim, Ruth and Kohelet with Targum, Rashi commentary, and compiled novellae, together with Bereshit with Targum and Rashi commentary, Haftarot, and leaves of Parshat Bereshit bound at the beginning and end of the manuscript. One manuscript has a gevil cover from the geniza of a Sefer Torah.','Three manuscripts, on paper and gevil, from Yemenite Jewry, comprising a compilation of Scriptures and Targum. The group includes three Megillot, Shir HaShirim, Ruth and Kohelet, with Targum, Rashi commentary, and compiled novellae attributed to Mahari Tzalach and others; Bereshit with Targum and Rashi commentary, with Haftarot; and Targum of Shir HaShirim, Ruth and Kohelet. Two of the manuscripts are approximately 23-24 cm in size. Leaves of Parshat Bereshit with Rashi commentary are bound at the beginning and end of one manuscript. One manuscript has a gevil cover from the geniza of a Sefer Torah.','https://www.kedem-auctions.com/en/content/three-manuscripts-yemen','kedem-auctions.com'),(206,'0- _22_p012_ec9c65d5','picture Auction 51 Part I - Books Chassidism Manuscripts Rabbinical Letters July 11, 2016 PDF Results Prices Realized Browse Sale << Previous Lot Lot 218 Next Lot >> Two Manuscripts, Prayers and Piyyutim - Yemen, 19th Century Opening: $450 Sold for: $625 Including buyer\'s premium Two Yemenite manuscripts, with original leather bindings. Ask about this lot Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents << Previous Lot Next Lot >> View Details Piyyutim of Bakashot, Tikun Chatzot, interpretation of dreams, tekufot and amulets, blessings and versions of shtarot, Birkat HaMazon with \"Chiddushin\", eulogies and a compilation of commentaries. Provenance: Collection of Willy Lindwer. Ancient leather binding with leather loops and adornments - worn, with worming. Scribe\'s colophon: \"Ya\'ish son of Yichye Al Tza\'adi\" from 1864. Ancient leather binding, with folk ornamentation, worn. Prayers, piyyutim of Selichot and Hosha\'anot.',600,625,'USD','Manuscript, paper, with original leather binding. Yemen, 19th century. Two Yemenite manuscripts containing prayers and piyyutim, including Bakashot, Tikun Chatzot, dream interpretation, tekufot and amulets, blessings and versions of shtarot, Birkat HaMazon with \"Chiddushin\", eulogies, and a compilation of commentaries. The binding is worn and shows worming.','Manuscript, paper, with original leather binding. Yemen, 19th century. Two Yemenite manuscripts with original leather bindings, containing piyyutim of Bakashot, Tikun Chatzot, interpretation of dreams, tekufot and amulets, blessings and versions of shtarot, Birkat HaMazon with \"Chiddushin\", eulogies, and a compilation of commentaries. The manuscripts also include prayers and piyyutim of Selichot and Hosha\'anot. One scribe\'s colophon names \"Ya\'ish son of Yichye Al Tza\'adi\" and is dated 1864. The bindings are described as ancient leather bindings with leather loops and adornments, worn and wormed, with folk ornamentation. Provenance: Collection of Willy Lindwer.','https://www.kedem-auctions.com/en/content/two-manuscripts-prayers-and-piyyutim-yemen-19th-century','kedem-auctions.com'),(207,'0- _22_p014_f8a5f56a','picture Auction 51 Part I - Books Chassidism Manuscripts Rabbinical Letters July 11, 2016 PDF Results Prices Realized Browse Sale << Previous Lot Lot 222 Next Lot >> Manuscript - Siddur for Year-round Use - Yemen, 19th Century Opening: $600 Sold for: $813 Including buyer\'s premium Manuscript, siddur for year-round use - for weekdays, Shabbat and festivals. Ask about this lot Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents << Previous Lot Next Lot >> View Details Contains prayers for weekdays and for Shabbat, prayers for Rosh Chodesh, Birkat HaLevana, Seder for Chanuka, Tikun Purim, Tikun Pesach with the Haggadah, prayers for the Three Festivals and Azharot for Shavuot. On verso of title page: \"Version of blessings and prayers, according to our tradition of the holy congregation throughout Yemenite cities\". Title page with illustrated frame: \"Siddur of prayers according to Sephardic tradition, and written for the entire year…\". The last 20 leaves (Approximately) [prayers for the Festival of Shavuot and Azharot] are in a different handwriting. Stains and wear, tears [affecting the text of several leaves]. Some leaves at the end were replaced in another handwriting.',602,NULL,'','Manuscript, siddur on paper for year-round use, Yemen, 19th century. Contains prayers for weekdays, Shabbat, festivals, Rosh Chodesh, Birkat HaLevana, Seder for Chanuka, Tikun Purim, Tikun Pesach with the Haggadah, the Three Festivals, and Azharot for Shavuot.','Manuscript, siddur on paper for year-round use, Yemen, 19th century. The manuscript includes prayers for weekdays and Shabbat, prayers for Rosh Chodesh, Birkat HaLevana, Seder for Chanuka, Tikun Purim, Tikun Pesach with the Haggadah, prayers for the Three Festivals, and Azharot for Shavuot. The verso of the title page bears the note: \"Version of blessings and prayers, according to our tradition of the holy congregation throughout Yemenite cities\". The title page has an illustrated frame and is inscribed: \"Siddur of prayers according to Sephardic tradition, and written for the entire year…\". The last approximately 20 leaves, containing prayers for the Festival of Shavuot and Azharot, are in a different handwriting, and some leaves at the end were replaced in another handwriting. The manuscript shows stains, wear, and tears affecting the text of several leaves.','https://www.kedem-auctions.com/en/content/manuscript-siddur-year-round-use-yemen-19th-century','kedem-auctions.com'),(208,'0- _22_p015_88c123d1','picture Auction 51 Part I - Books Chassidism Manuscripts Rabbinical Letters July 11, 2016 PDF Results Prices Realized Browse Sale << Previous Lot Lot 224 Next Lot >> Three Manuscripts - Yemen Opening: $400 Sold for: $1,000 Including buyer\'s premium Three small volumes of manuscripts, with compilations of various topics. Ask about this lot Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents << Previous Lot Next Lot >> View Details Manuscript, compilation by various writers and from various times: story of Jesus, leap years, death of Aharon the Cohen, oaths, te\'amim according to Kabbalah, etc. Manuscript, compilation by various writers and from various times: laws of shechita, Shabbat songs, te\'amim, etc. Part of the Passover Haggadah appears in the beginning of the manuscript [in another handwriting]. Three volumes of manuscripts, approximately 200 leaves. Manuscript, Birkat Erusin, piyyutim, bakashot.',603,1000,'USD','Manuscript, paper, three small volumes of manuscripts from Yemen, comprising compilations by various writers and from various times on diverse topics, including the story of Jesus, leap years, the death of Aharon the Cohen, oaths, te\'amim according to Kabbalah, laws of shechita, Shabbat songs, part of the Passover Haggadah, Birkat Erusin, piyyutim, and bakashot.','Manuscript, paper, three small volumes of manuscripts from Yemen, compiled by various writers and from various times. The contents include the story of Jesus, leap years, the death of Aharon the Cohen, oaths, te\'amim according to Kabbalah, laws of shechita, Shabbat songs, and a section of the Passover Haggadah in another hand at the beginning of one manuscript. The group comprises approximately 200 leaves in total. One manuscript also contains Birkat Erusin, piyyutim, and bakashot.','https://www.kedem-auctions.com/en/content/three-manuscripts-yemen-0','kedem-auctions.com'),(209,'0- _22_p016_cc4b6a73','picture picture 2 PHOTOS Auction 51 Part I - Books Chassidism Manuscripts Rabbinical Letters July 11, 2016 PDF Results Prices Realized Browse Sale << Previous Lot Lot 225 Next Lot >> Collection of Manuscripts - Yemen Opening: $800 Sold for: $1,750 Including buyer\'s premium Collection of eight manuscripts. Ask about this lot Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents Yemenite Jewry - Manuscripts and Documents << Previous Lot Next Lot >> View Details Torah and Megillot, Passover Haggadot and prayers. Some have old bindings and others are newly bound. For a complete list, see Hebrew description.',604,1750,'USD','Manuscript collection, paper and bindings, comprising eight manuscripts from Yemen. The group includes Torah and Megillot, Passover Haggadot, and prayers; some volumes have old bindings and others are newly bound.','Manuscript collection, paper and bindings, comprising eight manuscripts from Yemen. The group includes Torah and Megillot, Passover Haggadot, and prayers. The manuscripts are described as a collection of eight items, with some volumes retaining old bindings and others newly bound. The source identifies the material as manuscripts and notes their association with Yemenite Jewry and manuscripts and documents.','https://www.kedem-auctions.com/en/content/collection-manuscripts-yemen','kedem-auctions.com'),(210,'0- _22_p017_6abd9361','How to sell 269 — Five Roman glass vessels 5 £500 - £700 270 — Eight Roman glass vessels 8 £1,500 - £2,000 19 — A Late Roman or B