ck and an oval face with stylised facial features, including arching incised eyebrows above almond-shaped eyes inlaid with white stone, a long straight nose, and a small mouth. The hair falls behind semi-circular ears and the head is set on an alabaster stepped base.','Head, alabaster. South Arabian Qatabanian alabaster head of a woman, circa 1st century B.C./A.D. The object is carved with a long neck and an oval face, the features rendered in a stylised manner. It has arching incised eyebrows above almond-shaped eyes inlaid with white stone, a long straight nose, and a small mouth below. The hair falls behind semi-circular ears. The head is mounted on an alabaster stepped base. The overall height, including the base, is 29.5 cm.','https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/23364/lot/147/','bonhams.com'),(217,'0- _22_p024_df087257','Find your local specialist Ask about this lot Matthew Thomas Senior Specialist Tel: +44 20 7468 8270 [email protected] Two carved wood Panels Yemen, 14th Century rectangular, carved with relief with thuluth script and below a band of raised hemispheres the largest 56 x 24 cm. Previous Lot Next Lot Lot 41 Two carved wood Panels Yemen, 14th Century (2) Islamic and Indian Art 7 October 2014, 10:30 BST London, New Bond Street £2,000 - £3,000 Own a similar item? Buyers\' Premium and Charges For all Sales categories, buyer\'s premium excluding Cars, Motorbikes, Wine, Whisky and Coin & Medal sales, will be as follows: Buyer\'s Premium Rates 28% on the first £40,000 of the hammer price',612,NULL,'','Panels, wood. Two rectangular carved wood panels from Yemen, dated to the 14th century, carved in relief with thuluth script and a band of raised hemispheres below.','Panels, wood. Two rectangular carved wood panels from Yemen, dated to the 14th century. The panels are carved in relief with thuluth script and a band of raised hemispheres below. The largest panel measures 56 x 24 cm. The source identifies two panels and gives no further technical or contextual details.','https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/21722/lot/41','bonhams.com'),(218,'0- _22_p030_cb31daf3','LOT 123 A Sabaean marble head and torso of a youth [ translate ] A Sabaean marble head and torso of a youth, South Arabia, c. Interested bidders are strongly encouraged to request a condition report on any lots upon which they intend to bid, prior to placing a bid, and we will be happy to give you a full overview of the items\' condition. Condition: The absence of a condition statement does not imply that the lot is in perfect condition or completely free from wear and tear, imperfections , the effects of aging, or repair/restoration work. 3rd - 1st Century BC, possessing large eyes and nose, his elbows at his side, fists clenched forward. All transactions are governed by Ancient Resource LLC\'s Conditions of Sale. Nice mineral deposits within the recesses.',616,NULL,'','Marble head and torso of a youth, Sabaean, South Arabia, 3rd-1st century BC. The figure has large eyes and nose, with elbows at the sides and fists clenched forward.','Marble head and torso of a youth, Sabaean, South Arabia, 3rd-1st century BC. The figure is described as possessing large eyes and a prominent nose, with the elbows held at the sides and the fists clenched forward. Nice mineral deposits are present within the recesses. No further condition details are provided in the source text.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/A-Sabaean-marble-head-and-torso-of-a-youth/123-sabaean_marble-30.5.20-ancientres','lot-art.com'),(219,'29- _29_p019_5186eca2','Bull Protome Qataban Kingdom, Yemen 700-100 BC Bronze Height : 18 cm Provenance : Sotheby\'s New York, 1999, lot 84 Galerie David Ghezelbash, Paris (acquired from above) Private collection, Paris Publication : Kunstkammer, 2017, n°3 In the shape of the powerful forequarters of a bull, his massive head with round muzzle, grooved nostrils, and ribbed bulging brows, symbolic motifs and a crescent moon engraved on the forehead, a lozenge-decorated diadem between the horns. The national god of each of the kingdoms or states was the Moon-god known by various names: ‘Ilumquh by the Sabaeans, ‘Amm and ‘Anbay by the Qatabanians, Wadd (love) by the Minaeans, and Sin by the Hadramis”. Amongst the South Arabians the worship of the moon continued, and it is almost certain that their religious calendar was also lunar and that their years were calculated by the position of the moon. This rare Sabean inscription is dedicated to the moon god and refers to the people of Qataban, the most prominent Yemeni kingdom in the second half of the 1st millenium before Christ. This, combined with the use of a star calendar by the agriculturists of certain parts, particularly in the Hadramaut, indicates that there was an early reverence for the night sky. Muller, from the Center for Near and Middle-Eastern studies of Philipps Univeristy of Marburg, describes in detail the context and the meaning of these different motifs. “The South Arabians before Islam were polytheists and revered a large number of deities. It was essentially a planetary system in which the moon as a masculine deity prevailed.',619,NULL,'','Bull protome, bronze, Qataban Kingdom, Yemen, 700-100 BC. Height 18 cm. The object is formed as the powerful forequarters of a bull, with a massive head, round muzzle, grooved nostrils, ribbed bulging brows, engraved symbolic motifs, a crescent moon on the forehead, and a lozenge-decorated diadem between the horns.','Bull protome, bronze, Qataban Kingdom, Yemen, 700-100 BC. Height 18 cm. The object is shaped as the powerful forequarters of a bull, with a massive head, round muzzle, grooved nostrils, and ribbed bulging brows. The forehead is engraved with symbolic motifs and a crescent moon, and a lozenge-decorated diadem is placed between the horns. The source text identifies it as a rare Sabean inscription dedicated to the moon god and referring to the people of Qataban, the most prominent Yemeni kingdom in the second half of the 1st millennium BC.','https://www.martindoustar.com/archeology?pgid=k7xd5qk7-380a65b1-4910-4978-a221-508898191e05','martindoustar.com'),(220,'29- _29_p021_11b31839','Since almost all warriors from the rims of vessels as well as figures in appliqué on the shoulders of craters are shown moving from left to right, our figure probably had a counterpart facing him on the edge of a vessel or belonged to a free-standing group. If there was trade with Arabia in incense, myrrh and other spices in the 6th century B.C., it would have been conducted by East Greeks, but the figure might easily have passed from hand to hand via Egypt or the Levant. Published: Beazley, J.D.: An Archaic Greek Statuette from South Arabia, BSA 40, 1939-40 (publ. The double moulding on the left side of the helmet crest seems not to have been repeated on the right side, if this be so, the figure is to be seen from the left. - Jucker, H.: Bronzehenkel und Bronzehydria aus Pesaro, StOliv 13-14, 1966, p. Warrior - Archaic 47/103 Down Bronze H: 17 cm From Yemen Laconian? M.: Statuettes de bronze de Lykosoura, BCH 99, 1975, no. 1 Berlin, Antikenmuseum 7470: Neugebauer, K.-A.: Die griechischen Bronzen der klassischen Zeit und des Hellenismus (Berlin, 1951), no.',620,NULL,'','Bronze statuette of a warrior, Archaic period, 17 cm high, from Yemen. The figure is described as facing left, with a helmet crest showing double moulding on the left side only.','Bronze statuette of a warrior, Archaic period, 17 cm high, from Yemen. The figure is identified as a warrior and is described as being seen from the left, since the double moulding on the left side of the helmet crest does not appear to have been repeated on the right side. It is suggested that the figure may originally have belonged to a larger composition, either as a counterpart to another figure on the rim of a vessel or as part of a free-standing group. The object has been discussed in relation to Laconian bronzes and published by Beazley and Jucker.','https://www.georgeortiz.com/objects/greek-world-cont/117-warrior-archaic/','georgeortiz.com'),(221,'29- _29_p043_255b10d7','Form Through Time Auction: 31 May 2023 at 15:00 BST £10,080 Description carved striped alabaster, the slender neck rising to a rounded chin, the face bearing a compact mouth, the upper lip topped with a small moustache, the ridge nose parting two almond shaped eyes below a sweeping incised brow, raised on a bespoke mount Dimensions 20.9cm tall (excluding stand) Provenance Provenance: Previously in the Private Collection of Mr François Antonovich (b. With the facial features stripped to the essence of form, it served as a votive object, and was intended to fit within a small rectangular niche within a ritual site, hence the flattened top of the head. Skip to main content Home My Auctions Menu Search My Favourites Lot 31 ANCIENT SABAEAN ARABIAN MALE HEAD SOUTHERN ARABIA, C. 1934), who spent much of his childhood in Cairo before setting up his gallery in Paris, assembled, from as early as 1964, a collection of South Arabian artefacts which has been known to scholars in the field for decades. Lot 31 ANCIENT SABAEAN ARABIAN MALE HEAD SOUTHERN ARABIA, C. and cover) The present piece is a fine example of the distinctive, enigmatic sculpture produced by the wealthy south Arabian kingdoms at the turn of the first millennium B.C. ANCIENT SABAEAN ARABIAN MALE HEAD SOUTHERN ARABIA, C. Footnote Published: Treasures from Ancient Yemen: On the Legendary Road of the Kingdom of Sheba, c.',625,NULL,'','Head, carved striped alabaster, with a slender neck, rounded chin, compact mouth, small moustache, ridge nose, almond-shaped eyes, and a sweeping incised brow, raised on a bespoke mount. Height 20.9 cm excluding stand.','Head, carved striped alabaster, with the facial features reduced to a simplified form: a slender neck rising to a rounded chin, a compact mouth with a small moustache above the upper lip, a ridge nose, almond-shaped eyes, and a sweeping incised brow. The top of the head is flattened. The object is raised on a bespoke mount and measures 20.9 cm high excluding the stand. The source text identifies it as an Ancient Sabaean Arabian male head from Southern Arabia, dated to around the turn of the first millennium B.C., and notes that it was intended to fit within a small rectangular niche within a ritual site, serving as a votive object.','https://www.lyonandturnbull.com/auctions/form-through-time-735/lot/31','lyonandturnbull.com'),(222,'0- _14_p022_e7ef2ce4','LOT 0206 South Arabian Alabaster Tablet with Inscription [ translate ] 3rd century B.C.-1st century A.D.. limestone block in the collection of the British Museum under accession no. The South Arabian script is an abjad written sinistrograde',627,NULL,'','Tablet, alabaster, with inscription. South Arabian script, written sinistrograde. Dated to the 3rd century B.C.-1st century A.D.','Tablet, alabaster, with inscription. The object is described as a South Arabian alabaster tablet and is associated with a limestone block in the collection of the British Museum under accession number not specified in the source text. The inscription is in South Arabian script, an abjad written sinistrograde. The object is dated to the 3rd century B.C.-1st century A.D.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/South-Arabian-Alabaster-Tablet-with-Inscription/206-south_arabian-05.9.23-timeline','lot-art.com'),(223,'0- _14_p026_2c507d36','Size:17 cm L - 6 11/16 inches Material:Alabaster Culture:South Arabian/Sabaean, c. LOT 0089 South Arabian/Sabaean Speckled Alabaster Calf, c. Very attractive alabaster speckled with grey, pink and white, carved in the shape of a calf standing on integral base. Near Eastern private collection, acquired and imported into the UK in the 1980s. [ translate ] South Arabian/Sabaean Speckled Alabaster Calf, c.',628,NULL,'','Calf, alabaster, South Arabian/Sabaean, carved in speckled alabaster with grey, pink and white tones, standing on an integral base. Length 17 cm (6 11/16 inches).','Calf, alabaster, South Arabian/Sabaean, carved in speckled alabaster with grey, pink and white tones and formed as a standing calf on an integral base. The object measures 17 cm in length (6 11/16 inches). The source text identifies it as South Arabian/Sabaean and notes a Near Eastern private collection provenance, acquired and imported into the UK in the 1980s.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/South-ArabianSabaean-Speckled-Alabaster-Calf--c-1st-Century-BC/89-south_arabian-30.5.23-artemission','lot-art.com'),(224,'0- _14_p027_ec708607','LOT 45 FOUR SOUTH ARABIAN ANIMAL FIGURES [ translate ] FOUR SOUTH ARABIAN ANIMAL FIGURES FOUR SOUTH ARABIAN ANIMAL FIGURES largest 12cm Past » View it on Login Estimate Unlock Reserve Unlock Time, Location 15 Jul 2022 UK, London Auction House Unlock [ translate ] FOUR SOUTH ARABIAN ANIMAL FIGURES FOUR SOUTH ARABIAN ANIMAL FIGURES largest 12cm Estimate Unlock Reserve Unlock Time, Location 15 Jul 2022 UK, London Auction House Unlock Past » View it on Login',629,NULL,'','Animal figures, South Arabian, largest 12 cm.','Animal figures, South Arabian, four in total, with the largest example measuring 12 cm. No further details on material, technique, date, or condition are provided in the source text.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/FOUR-SOUTH-ARABIAN-ANIMAL-FIGURES/45-four_south-15.7.22-plaka','lot-art.com'),(225,'0- _14_p028_4041cb1f','LOT 64 A SOUTH ARABIAN CARNELIAN INSCRIBED MAGICAL SCARBOID, CIRCA ... [ translate ] A SOUTH ARABIAN CARNELIAN INSCRIBED MAGICAL SCARBOID, CIRCA 3RD CENTURY A.D.',630,NULL,'','Scarboid, carnelian, South Arabian, inscribed magical, circa 3rd century A.D.','Scarboid, carnelian, South Arabian, inscribed magical, circa 3rd century A.D. The object is described as a scarboid made of carnelian and identified as South Arabian in origin. It bears an inscription and is characterized as magical. The dating given is circa the 3rd century A.D.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/A-SOUTH-ARABIAN-CARNELIAN-INSCRIBED-MAGICAL-SCARBOID--CIRCA-/64-south_arabian-03.7.23-plaka','lot-art.com'),(226,'0- _14_p029_f769888f','LOT 20 A South Arabian Alabaster Head of a Man, 3rd Century B.C./1st Century A.D. [ translate ] Property from the Collection of the late Antonin and Christiane Besse A South Arabian Alabaster Head of a Man 3rd Century B.C./1st Century A.D. Drilled underneath and mounted on a black marble base. Condition Report: As shown, note damages to chin and nose, slight abrasions to the ear rims. A large shallow chip in the back and CB 10 in black ink on the reverse. with large eyes recessed for inlay and grooved and drilled eyebrows.',631,NULL,'','Head, alabaster, South Arabian, of a man, 3rd century B.C./1st century A.D. Drilled underneath and mounted on a black marble base. The head has large eyes recessed for inlay and grooved, drilled eyebrows.','Head, alabaster, South Arabian, of a man, 3rd century B.C./1st century A.D. The object is drilled underneath and mounted on a black marble base. It has large eyes recessed for inlay and grooved, drilled eyebrows. Condition noted in the source includes damage to the chin and nose, slight abrasions to the ear rims, and a large shallow chip on the back. The reverse bears the inscription or mark \"CB 10\" in black ink.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/A-South-Arabian-Alabaster-Head-of-a-Man--3rd-Century-BC1st-Century-AD/20-south_arabian-07.12.21-sotheby','lot-art.com'),(227,'0- _14_p030_c5cb9878','one side of the architectural block carved in relief with the stylised frontal figures of five ibexes, each with straight legs in low relief, stepped muzzle, protruding circular eyes, and ribbed horns. LOT 2 A South Arabian Limestone Ibex Frieze, 3rd Century B.C./1st Century A.D. [ translate ] Property from the Collection of the late Antonin and Christiane Besse A South Arabian Limestone Ibex Frieze 3rd Century B.C./1st Century A.D. Condition Report: Heavily encrusted with some chips on lower part of three muzzles.',632,NULL,'','Architectural block, limestone, carved in relief on one side with the stylised frontal figures of five ibexes. Each ibex is shown with straight legs in low relief, a stepped muzzle, protruding circular eyes, and ribbed horns. South Arabian, 3rd century B.C./1st century A.D.','Architectural block, limestone, carved in relief on one side with a frieze of five stylised frontal ibexes. The animals are depicted with straight legs in low relief, stepped muzzles, protruding circular eyes, and ribbed horns. South Arabian, dated to the 3rd century B.C./1st century A.D. The object is heavily encrusted, with chips on the lower part of three muzzles.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/A-South-Arabian-Limestone-Ibex-Frieze--3rd-Century-BC1st-Century-AD/2-south_arabian-07.12.21-sotheby','lot-art.com'),(228,'0- _14_p032_82525ee5','LOT 19 A South Arabian Alabaster Relief Head of a Woman, circa 3rd Century B.C./1st Century A.D. [ translate ] Property from the Collection of the late Antonin and Christiane Besse A South Arabian Alabaster Relief Head of a Woman circa 3rd Century B.C./1st Century A.D. with large eyes inlaid with calcite and green stone (one remaining), grooved eyebrows, and long hair, and wearing a necklace.',633,NULL,'','Relief head, alabaster, South Arabian, circa 3rd century B.C./1st century A.D. Female head with large eyes inlaid with calcite and green stone, grooved eyebrows, long hair, and a necklace.','Relief head, alabaster, South Arabian, circa 3rd century B.C./1st century A.D. The object depicts a woman’s head in relief and is carved in alabaster. It has large eyes inlaid with calcite and green stone, with one inlay remaining, grooved eyebrows, long hair, and a necklace. The description identifies the piece as South Arabian and dates it to the circa 3rd century B.C./1st century A.D.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/A-South-Arabian-Alabaster-Relief-Head-of-a-Woman--circa-3rd-Century-BC1st-Century-AD/19-south_arabian-07.12.21-sotheby','lot-art.com'),(229,'0- _14_p035_4c0a409e','LOT 0075 South Arabian/Sabaean Marble Head Stele with Inscription, c. Size:10.8 cm L - 4 1/4 inches Material:Marble Culture:South Arabian/Sabaean, c. [ translate ] South Arabian/Sabaean Marble Head Stele with Inscription, c. Stelae were stone or wooden slabs erected in the ancient world as a monument, often used for funerary or commemorative purposes, government notices or as boundary markers. Alabaster funerary/memorial stele depicting a stylised face in high relief. On the forehead, the name inscribed upside-down in the tradition of tomb dedications with Sabaean letters reading the name of the person Sarhan â€˜SRHNâ€™. Flat forehead, bulging eyes, the extended eyebrows merging in the centre of the face into a long nose leading to a closed mouth with broad lips. The Sabaeans were a civilisation in South Arabia in pre-Islamic times, originally entering from the north.',634,NULL,'','Stele, marble, South Arabian/Sabaean, with inscription, 10.8 cm long. Funerary or memorial stele depicting a stylised face in high relief, with the name Sarhan (SRHN) inscribed upside-down on the forehead in Sabaean letters.','Stele, marble, South Arabian/Sabaean, with inscription, 10.8 cm long. Funerary or memorial stele depicting a stylised face in high relief. The face has a flat forehead, bulging eyes, extended eyebrows merging at the centre of the face into a long nose, and a closed mouth with broad lips. On the forehead, the name is inscribed upside-down in the tradition of tomb dedications, with Sabaean letters reading the name Sarhan (SRHN). The object is identified as South Arabian/Sabaean and dated broadly to the pre-Islamic period.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/South-ArabianSabaean-Marble-Head-Stele-with-Inscription--c-3rd-1st-Century-BC/75-south_arabian-28.2.23-artemission','lot-art.com'),(230,'0- _14_p036_90bc3926','A striking stone slab with a high-relief carved abstract face with a triangular nose, deep set oval eyes, a small mouth, prominent brow ridge and well-groomed eyebrows, and the suggestion of a crown or headdress. Size: L:370mm / W:195mm ',635,NULL,'','Stone slab with high-relief carved abstract face, showing a triangular nose, deep-set oval eyes, a small mouth, a prominent brow ridge, well-groomed eyebrows, and the suggestion of a crown or headdress. Dimensions: L: 370 mm; W: 195 mm.','Stone slab with high-relief carved abstract face, carved in stone and depicting a triangular nose, deep-set oval eyes, a small mouth, a prominent brow ridge, and well-groomed eyebrows, with the suggestion of a crown or headdress. The object is a slab form and measures 370 mm in length and 195 mm in width.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/SOUTH-ARABIAN-STONE-FACE-STELE-WITH-INLAID-EYES/492-south_arabian-12.3.23-apollo','lot-art.com'),(231,'0- _14_p037_d8eb0074','Hellenistic Period, 3rd - 2nd century BCE. LOT 330 A SOUTH ARABIAN BRONZE SCORPION. [ translate ] A SOUTH ARABIAN BRONZE SCORPION.',636,NULL,'','Scorpion, bronze, South Arabian, Hellenistic Period, 3rd–2nd century BCE.','Scorpion, bronze, South Arabian, Hellenistic Period, 3rd–2nd century BCE. The object is identified as a South Arabian bronze scorpion and is dated to the Hellenistic Period.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/A-SOUTH-ARABIAN-BRONZE-SCORPION/330-south_arabian-09.4.23-archaeological','lot-art.com'),(232,'0- _14_p038_e61326bd','An impressive and quite noble stone head presenting typical South Arabian characteristics of a somber countenance with almond-shaped eyes, arched brows, a straight nose, high cheekbones, and closed mouth, all flanked by a pair of high-set ears and a chin-length coiffure. Size: 2.4\" W x 2.5\" H (6.1 cm x 6.4 cm)',637,NULL,'','Stone head with typical South Arabian characteristics, showing a somber countenance, almond-shaped eyes, arched brows, a straight nose, high cheekbones, a closed mouth, high-set ears, and a chin-length coiffure. Dimensions: 2.4 in W x 2.5 in H (6.1 cm x 6.4 cm).','Stone head with typical South Arabian characteristics, carved with a somber countenance, almond-shaped eyes, arched brows, a straight nose, high cheekbones, and a closed mouth. The head is flanked by a pair of high-set ears and has a chin-length coiffure. Dimensions are 2.4 in W x 2.5 in H (6.1 cm x 6.4 cm).','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/South-Arabian-Stone-Head/98-south_arabian-11.5.23-artemi','lot-art.com'),(233,'0- _14_p039_ddf060e7','Carved in high relief protruding from a rectangular plaque with the lower section missing, the details of the bull\'s head including the eyes, brows and muzzle are incised, the small ears are carved in lower relief behind the horns one of which is missing, 16.4cm high, Provenance: Property from the collection of Mr and Mrs P. [ translate ] SOUTH ARABIAN ALABASTER STELE FRAGMENT WITH A BULL HEAD Circa 1st Century B.C. LOT 142 SOUTH ARABIAN ALABASTER STELE FRAGMENT WITH A BULL...',638,NULL,'','Stele fragment, alabaster, carved in high relief from a rectangular plaque with the lower section missing. The fragment depicts a bull head with incised eyes, brows, and muzzle; the small ears are carved in lower relief behind the horns, one of which is missing. Height 16.4 cm. South Arabian, circa 1st century B.C.','Stele fragment, alabaster, carved in high relief from a rectangular plaque with the lower section missing. The surviving decoration consists of a bull head protruding from the plaque, with the details of the eyes, brows, and muzzle incised. The small ears are carved in lower relief behind the horns, one of which is missing. The object measures 16.4 cm in height. It is identified as South Arabian and dated to circa 1st century B.C.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/SOUTH-ARABIAN-ALABASTER-STELE-FRAGMENT-WITH-A-BULL/142-south_arabian-29.6.18-chiswick','lot-art.com'),(234,'0- _14_p040_58885c6e','LOT 36685059 South Arabian Limestone Stele Fragment [ translate ] A finely engraved stone relief fragment features a naturalistically sculpted human face, featuring long eyebrows, elongated, almond-shaped eyes and prominent nose. 8cm width Provenance: Private German collection, Cologne. This object would have once been part of a large monumental stone relief. B: All items sold will come with their own Certificate of Authenticity, including the item\'s description, image and provenance. These types of anthropomorphic stelae have been recovered in funerary areas across the South Arabian peninsula. All items when shipped (if required) will be declared as antiquities over 100 years old and their valued price. Please also note, for insurance purposes, an items value cannot be under- declared.',639,NULL,'','Limestone stele fragment, finely engraved, with a naturalistically sculpted human face showing long eyebrows, elongated almond-shaped eyes, and a prominent nose. Width: 8 cm.','Limestone stele fragment, finely engraved, preserving a naturalistically sculpted human face with long eyebrows, elongated almond-shaped eyes, and a prominent nose. The object measures 8 cm in width. It is described as a fragment of a larger monumental stone relief. Anthropomorphic stelae of this type have been recovered in funerary areas across the South Arabian peninsula. Provenance: private German collection, Cologne.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/South-Arabian-Limestone-Stele-Fragment/36685059-south_arabian-07.5.20-catawiki','lot-art.com'),(235,'0- _14_p041_6240297d','LOT 69 A South Arabian Alabaster Ibex Height 5 3/8 inches (14 cm). Antiquities Height with stand 5.8 inches (15 cm). [ translate ] A South Arabian Alabaster Ibex Circa 1st Century A.D.',640,NULL,'','Ibex, alabaster, South Arabian, circa 1st century A.D. Height 5 3/8 inches (14 cm); height with stand 5.8 inches (15 cm).','Ibex, alabaster, South Arabian, circa 1st century A.D. The object is described as an ibex carved in alabaster. Its height is given as 5 3/8 inches (14 cm), and the height with stand is recorded as 5.8 inches (15 cm).','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/A-South-Arabian-Alabaster-Ibex-Height-5-38-inches-14-cm/69-south_arabian-26.5.22-hindman','lot-art.com'),(236,'0- _14_p042_78ff3cb5','LOT 70 A South Arabian Limestone Stele Height 14 3/8 inches (36.3 cm). Property from a New Jersey Private Collection Antiquities Height with stand 17.5 inches (44.5 cm)',641,NULL,'','Stele, limestone, South Arabian. Height 14 3/8 inches (36.3 cm); height with stand 17.5 inches (44.5 cm).','Stele, limestone, South Arabian. The object is a limestone stele attributed to South Arabia. It measures 14 3/8 inches (36.3 cm) in height, with a total height of 17.5 inches (44.5 cm) including the stand. The source text notes provenance from a New Jersey private collection of antiquities.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/A-South-Arabian-Limestone-Stele-Height-14-38-inches-363-cm/70-south_arabian-26.5.22-hindman','lot-art.com'),(237,'0- _14_p043_1add3b82','The plaque preserves twelve lines of inscription in raised relief, reading, \"Yin\'am and his brother and their sons the Banu Rasham have dedicated to their god LBNH, bull of M\'RBN, in his sanctuary at Sim\'ân, an inscription of divine ordinance which he has ordered for them in his property, for their wellbeing and the wellbeing of all that he has acquired and that he will acquire, and so that LBHN increases their prosperity and favour and health and strength and so that evil and wrong and also ill-will and injustice WTRKS and \'W/\'F of an enemy both far and near will be moved away from them\". LOT 255 A South Arabian bronze inscriptional plaque [ translate ] A South Arabian bronze inscriptional plaque Circa 1st Century A.D. 23.5cm high, 15.7cm wide Provenance: Private collection, Germany. Anonymous sale',642,NULL,'','Plaque, bronze. South Arabian bronze inscriptional plaque with twelve lines of inscription in raised relief, recording a dedication by Yin\'am, his brother, and their sons the Banu Rasham to their god LBNH, bull of M\'RBN, in his sanctuary at Sim\'ân. Circa 1st century A.D.; 23.5 cm high, 15.7 cm wide.','Plaque, bronze. South Arabian bronze inscriptional plaque preserving twelve lines of inscription in raised relief. The text records that Yin\'am, his brother, and their sons the Banu Rasham dedicated the plaque to their god LBNH, bull of M\'RBN, in his sanctuary at Sim\'ân, as an inscription of divine ordinance ordered for them in his property, for their wellbeing and the wellbeing of all that he has acquired and will acquire, and for the removal of evil, wrong, ill-will, injustice, WTRKS, and \'W/\'F of an enemy both far and near. Circa 1st century A.D. Dimensions: 23.5 cm high, 15.7 cm wide.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/A-South-Arabian-bronze-inscriptional-plaque/255-south_arabian-06.7.23-bonham','lot-art.com'),(238,'0- _14_p044_dfa1c7a5','LOT 256 A South Arabian limestone female figure [ translate ] A South Arabian limestone female figure Circa 3rd Century B.C.-1st Century A.D. The face of this figure retains remnants of a dark resin, which can also be seen on another female figure from the British Museum, acc. 24cm high Provenance: The Difilippantonio collection, Pennsylvania, collected between the 1980s and mid 1990s, and thence by descent. Chemical analysis of the British Museum example has shown that the brown coating on the face contains plant oils and conifer resins, suggesting that the substance was either a conifer resin varnish mixed with oils, or an oil perfumed with resin, and applied in thick layers. Connecticut Estates Auction',643,NULL,'','Female figure, limestone, South Arabian, circa 3rd century B.C.–1st century A.D. The face retains remnants of a dark resin. Height 24 cm.','Female figure, limestone, South Arabian, circa 3rd century B.C.–1st century A.D. The figure is made of limestone and preserves remnants of a dark resin on the face. The source text notes that a comparable female figure in the British Museum has a brown coating identified by chemical analysis as containing plant oils and conifer resins, suggesting either a conifer resin varnish mixed with oils or an oil perfumed with resin applied in thick layers. The object is recorded as 24 cm high.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/A-South-Arabian-limestone-female-figure/256-south_arabian-06.7.23-bonham','lot-art.com'),(239,'0- _14_p045_fd5a4154','[ translate ] SOUTH ARABIAN BRONZE HEAD OF A BULL Ḥimyarite Kingdom, 1st century BC - 1st century AD height cm 8,5',644,NULL,'','Bronze head of a bull, South Arabian, Ḥimyarite Kingdom, 1st century BC to 1st century AD. Height 8.5 cm.','Bronze head of a bull, South Arabian, from the Ḥimyarite Kingdom, dated to the 1st century BC to the 1st century AD. The object is recorded with a height of 8.5 cm.','https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/SOUTH-ARABIAN-BRONZE-HEAD-OF-A-BULL-imyarite-Kingdom--1st/258-south_arabian-10.7.19-bertolami','lot-art.com'),(240,'0- _15_p026_22dd2aa6','Dimensions W 1.6 cm Metal Gold Region Near East (Western Asiatic) Reference: For a similar item: Bonhams, London, Antiquities Auction, 24th October 2012, lot 201 You may also like… £ 1,100.00 Western Asiatic Gold Pair of Earrings View product £ 700.00 Western Asiatic Electrum Cluster Pendant View product Ancient South Arabia is a geographical label referring to a region occupied by six semitic kingdoms: Sabaʼ, Qatabān, Ma‘īn, Ḥaḍramawt, the Kingdom of Awsan, and the Himyarite Kingdom. SKU: NES-127 Category: Near Eastern Tag: Male Figures Description Additional information Ancient South Arabia is a geographical label referring to a region occupied by six semitic kingdoms: Sabaʼ, Qatabān, Ma‘īn, Ḥaḍramawt, the Kingdom of Awsan, and the Himyarite Kingdom. The territory of these kingdoms corresponds to a modern-day area including Yemen, and extending into Oman, north to the Arabian oasis of Dedan, to Ethiopia, and even as far along as the East African Coast, into modern Tanzania. Date: Circa 2nd Century AD Provenance: Acquired 1970-1999. Comprised of a thick D-shaped hoop which flares outwards at the shoulders before widening to encompass the bezel. To discover more about jewellery in the Ancient World, please visit our relevant post: Jewellery in Antiquity. South Arabian Gold Child’s Ring £ 3,000.00 A South Arabian gold ring featuring a decorated, oval bezel. Incised lines have been used to create the particles of his hair, tied with a filet.',669,NULL,'','Ring, gold, from Near East (Western Asiatic), circa 2nd century AD. Thick D-shaped hoop flaring at the shoulders and widening to encompass the bezel.','Ring, gold, from Ancient South Arabia in the Near East (Western Asiatic), dated circa 2nd century AD. The object has a thick D-shaped hoop that flares outwards at the shoulders before widening to encompass the bezel. The source text also notes a decorated, oval bezel, with incised lines used to create the particles of the hair, tied with a filet. Provenance is given as acquired 1970–1999.','https://www.ancient-art.co.uk/near-eastern/south-arabian-gold-childs-ring','ancient-art.co.uk');
